animal.description:
Tassie is a shy mama terrier mix who was rescued from a hoarding home with over 40 dogs. We believe she is roughly 2 1/2 years old. She spent her life in a backyard and was never socialized. She was abused by the husband and 2 sons in the home. After her puppies were placed in adoptive homes, Tassie has been learning how to be a house dog and learning about the perks of living in a human home full of affection.

Tassie has been thriving in her foster home and is learning to love toys, bully sticks and running around. She's definitely come into her own and is a playful little diva. She's currently being fostered with other dogs, peacocks, pigs and chickens! Boy has her life turned around!!

Tassie is fostered in Sonoma County, CA and will be available to adopt from Santa Rosa 95403 at a pre-approved, scheduled appoinment. Due to COVID-19 we are NOT doing any meet and greets at this time.

If you are interseted in adopting Tassie, please email an application to start that process to softpawsrescue@gmail.com. You can find our application at www.softpawsrescue.org/applytoadopt , please also attach pictures of the inside of your home (anyplace the dog would be) as well as your front and backyards.

A note from Tassies foster mom: Tassie may take a little bit to warm up, but is super affectionate, cuddly and loyal once shes comfortable. She is happy cuddling on the couch in bed for the majority of the day. As shes come out of her shell, shes become more playful and is still in the process of figuring out doggy toys. She is so incredibly snuggly and would LOVE to sleep on the bed with her owners. Shes not technically house trained but if you stick to a regular walk/backyard schedule she doesnt have accidents in the house. Shes had positive encounters with calm, friendly, dogs and is becoming confident around them. She loves her bully sticks and will collect them and corral them around the house. She is still unsure about young children and men. Overall she is an incredible dog that has made leaps and bounds of progress since being with her foster family. Were confident that she will make a patient, loving family incredibly happy.

animal.description: Sweet Tia is looking for her forever Netflix partner. This golden gal wants nothing more than to sit on the couch and snuggle with her humans. As an older lady, she doesn't require tons of exercise, so if you think you might be too lazy for a dog, you should meet Tia! Tia is very intuitive, and can tell when her humans had a rough day and need extra snuggles - how cool is that?! She is house-trained, and will let you know when she needs to go outside by letting out a quick bark or by standing at the door. Otherwise, she really doesn't bark much. She's worked on her tricks and really wants to show off that she knows how to 'shake.' Plus, she does great when left home alone. Tia would do best as the only pup in the house - she can provide enough emotional support to her humans, and she wants to be the top dog! Tia loves her humans and has so much love to give to the right home. Her ideal home would be one with a yard where she can run around with her humans. Come meet your new snuggle buddy Tia! She would love to binge watch that new Netflix series with you.

animal.description:
SHAMUS is a friendly, 2-year-old, 60-pound, German Shorthaired Pointer and Red Tick Coonhound mix.

He's a good-natured and social fellow who loves being in the company of children and other dogs.

SHAMUS is undergoing treatment for heartworm disease - he'll be as good-as-new in no time!

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster, or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing THE FIRST STEP IN ADOPTING A SNARR DOG IS FILLING OUT AN APPLICATION AT WWW.SNARRNORTHEAST.ORG/APPLICATIONS.****

Name: Penny

Age: 2 years

Current Weight: 46 lbs

Rescued from: Tennessee

Health: up to date on required vaccinations, spayed, microchipped

Adoption fee: $375

Penny is a loving and lively 2 year old redbone coonhound mix with a beautiful deep red coat, soulful eyes and a joyful disposition. Those eyes make her look serious, but she is all about fun! This smart and social gal thrives on interaction and activity. She’s a great sidekick who likes to go everywhere with her people (she settles right in in the car), and makes friends wherever she goes. 

Penny loves to play, and is looking for a home with a fenced yard and a canine buddy. (She is not a cat person). Her leash walking skills are excellent, she knows basic commands and she’s very eager to please -particularly for treats! True to her coonhound heritage, she’s inclined to be vocal when she’s excited, but she is making good progress learning to redirect her attention. Pretty Penny is ready to find an active forever home where she can truly shine. 

To apply to adopt Penny, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, so there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults / Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
AVAILABLE FOR FOSTER to ADOPT
PLEASE read this BIOGRAPHY CAREFULLY.  It will answer most of your questions including why Georgia Liberty is Foster-to-Adopt.

House Trained?  Yes
Crate Trained?   Yes
Good on Leash? Yes
Energy Level?     Medium
Good with other nice dogs?   Yes
Good with Adults?  yes
Good with Older Children?  Yes

GEORGIA LIBERTY, named after one of the best states in the USA, is the perfect package!  She is just old enough at 1.5 years old to not be considered a puppy, so she has outgrown chewing things and is completely house-trained.  She is the perfect medium-sized dog, and full grown. 

GEORGIA is one smart and beautiful dog with very nice manners to match! She is very intelligent and knows how to sit and take treat very gently from your hand.  She has a happy and extremely sweet personality.  At times, she still gets bursts of puppy energy and wants to do "zoomies," but is also content to relax next to you.  Georgia is crate trained, potty trained, and is learning to walk well on a leash.  Many nights, she puts herself to bed in her crate, and she sleeps quietly all night until her foster mom opens the door in the morning. 

She gets very excited around meal time and as soon as she sees her bowl, she runs and waits patiently for her food in her crate like a good girl.   Georgia likes to play with other nice dogs and would be fine as an only dog or with other dogs. Her current foster home has 3 other dogs and Georgia gets along with all of them.    

Georgia loves all people.  She has three older children /teens in her foster home and enjoys following them around.  She would be fine with younger children too, but she is still learning to not jump on people when they first meet her.  A small child may accidentally get jumped on with no intention of hurting. Georgia's foster mom has been using a spray bottle with water to deter this behavior, and she is learning quickly.  

What is FOSTER TO ADOPT, you ask?  When a dog has not yet been altered (spayed or neutered) due to a medical treatment that is in process, but there is someone that wants to bring that dog into their family as an adopted family member, we approve the adopter as a FOSTER HOME, complete the medical treatment and spay, and then finalize the adoption.

This will allow GEORGIA LIBERTY to be placed with her forever family so there is no delay in the bonding process while You Lucky Dog Rescue remains responsible for the completion of the remaining vetting needs.

What is GEORGIA's MEDICAL CONDITION?  She is heart worm positive - very common with shelter dogs as in most cases, their former humans just didn't care enough to provide them with monthly heart worm preventative.  Like any parasite, medical treatment will take care of those nasty worms, but it is a process. As soon as her treatment is completed, Georgia will be spayed. We can then finalize your adoption of Georgia.  

She will need a nurturing family to care for her during treatment as her activity level will need to be restricted during that time.  If you have another dog in the home,  you will need to keep her separated from active play with other dogs - JUST UNTIL  treatment is completed. After treatment, she can resume normal play and other exercise activities.
 
If you Foster-To-Adopt Georgia, you will be fully supported by our volunteers that have all been through the heart worm treatment process with other dogs.  And, we cover the expense of treatment!  100%.

Georgia has an estimated DOB of 7/14/19 and is believed to be a 
Lab Retriever/American Staffordshire Terrier mix.  She weighed 58 pounds  at her last vet visit. 

If you live in the Greater Metro ATL, GA area and are interested in  Fostering To 
Adopt Georgia, please email us at info@youluckydogrescue.org and visit our website to submit an online FOSTER APPLICATION - we cover all medical/vetting expenses, supply a loaner crate, if needed.  We also provide leash/collars/tag and monthly heart worm and flea preventatives until the adoption is finalized. - as well as the cost of heart worm treatment.

FOSTER APPLICATION:  YOULUCKYDOGRESCUE.ORG

QUESTIONS - yep, we know you got 'em!  Email us at info@youluckydogrescue.org

Our adoption fee is $300 and includes all age appropriate vaccines, spay  or neuter and microchipping.   The breed and age included in this listing is based upon the opinion of a vet that has examined the dog.  We cannot confirm the age of the dog unless the dog was born in the care of the rescue.  We are located in the metro Atlanta area.   We currently do not allow out of state adoptions as a home check is required as part of the adoption process.

This is Diamond. She has had a rough life, she was adopted from the shelter as a puppy, and found herself at the same shelter at 3 years old. She showed up with a broke leg that healed incorrectly, and bb pellets in her leg. Her leg required amputation because her previous owner allowed it to heal so poorly, it wasn’t fixable.

She is approximately 3 years old, 50lbs, short in stature, compact, but beefy. She is GREAT with children, and she doesn’t let her missing leg slow her down.

Recently she has developed some leash reactivity to other dogs and needs a confident handler to help her work through these issues when she sees other dogs in public. Initially she was great with other dogs in our rescue, so we have faith she can get back to that point,

She is crate trained. Walks well on leash, and she knows her basic commands.

animal.description:
This gorgeous girl is a Pup Squad momma - a very special Pup Squad momma.  

Gentry found herself trying to survive on her own in Houston's East End when she was barely more than a pup.  A Pup Squad adopter spotted her and started working to gain her trust through patience and snacks. It was a very slow process which gained increased urgency when we realized Gentry was pregnant. Unfortunately, she was not cooperative. She'd come into the yard to hang out and even use the crate and blankets when it was cold, or rainy, but as soon as people got close, she was outta there.

Then, Gentry chose to have her babies right there, so we were able to scoop her and her babies up and get them inside. Gentry raised a litter of gorgeous pups who all quickly found their forever homes. So, we started working with Gentry to help her get ready for her forever home.

Gentry has been staying at a special rescue boarding facility where she has doggy friends who have helped her learn that humans aren't so bad after all. 

Gentry is still shy with people, but she's come such a long way. She is ready for her forever home.  Gentry definitely needs at least one doggy friend and she needs a quiet home with patient humans.

Gentry's approx. DOB is 6/1/2018.

Our adoption fee is a $250.00 donation to Pup Squad Animal Rescue. Our adopted dogs are all spayed/neutered, vaccinated and micro-chipped. If you are interested in adoption, please go to www.pupsquad.org/adopt to read more about our policies and find our application. Applications should be submitted via the online form http://pupsquad.org/adopt/adoption-application.html.

During COVID 19 - We may not be able to help coordinate transport out of state due to limited resources on our end and limited transport options to get the dogs to destinations outside of Texas.

Thank you for choosing to rescue an animal in need!
www.pupsquad.org

animal.description:
MAXWELL
Shepherd Mix
(DOB: 05/28/20)

Introducing Maxwell. He is a young Shepherd mix and weighs just under 20 lbs. Maxwell is so handsome and look at those ears – super cute. Maxwell is a beautiful, loving, playful boy.

Maxwell's favorite toys are a Nylabone that looks like a stick and a Kong ball. He enjoys the company of other dogs – he plays well with others, although he is known to swipe a toy or two from his foster fur-buddies. He's pretty strong for his size. 

Maxwell's most endearing habit/quality is his strong cuddle game. He is a total cuddle-bug! 

3 words to describe Maxwell's personality:
1. Energetic
2. Smart
3. Cuddly

Maxwell is working on his basic obedience skills. His foster family have already trained him to SIT and play FETCH. He is crate-trained and house-trained (except when it's raining). He knows his name and will come when called.

Some things Maxwell is still working on:  Shoes – he is fascinated with shoes.  He can find every single one in the house that hasn't been put away! Maxwell is also working on eating independently. Sometimes his foster mom will hand feed him to get him started.

Maxwell is a little unsure around new people. He is a bit stand offish at first, but once he's sees that you're ok, he comes right up. Maxwell likes women better than men.

Maxwell is great with kids and loves to play with them. He is up-to-date on vaccines, neutered, microchipped and being maintained on monthly heartworm and flea/tick prevention. 

Some nicknames we call Maxwell are:
Max
Maxi
Maximilian

Our best time of day together is evening/night. After dinner we go for a walk with the other fur-friends in the house. Then its playtime followed by a good cuddle session then off to bed.

Maxwell needs an understanding owner who can work with him to become more independent and who has time to be home with him for part of the day.

This dog is currently being fostered as part of Diamonds in the Ruff Canine Rescue. An application is required, along with a home visit and small adoption fee.  Applicants must be at least 21 years of age. **FENCED IN YARD REQUIRED**

Please visit us on our Facebook page for additional photos, give us a like while you're there! 
https://www.facebook.com/diamondsintheruffNC

All of our dogs are fostered in homes and are INDOOR dogs. We believe all dogs are family members and should be treated as valued members of the household. 

Please review our adoption guidelines for further information on adopting from Diamonds in the Ruff Canine Rescue before submitting an application. www.DITRnc.com.


.

animal.description:
BJ is 8 years old, and 56 lbs.  He arrived at the NYCACC, the NYC Municipal shelter as an owner surrender.  After 8 years, his owners gave him up. He then landed on the euthanasia list where he almost lost his life.  

Fortunately he was saved because an amazing woman offered to foster him.

This is what she says about him:

Bj is a great dog, housetrained, and no destruction. Very well behaved in the house. No accidents. Quiet as can be. If someone knocks at the door he does however have a very strange bark. Not loud but strange...lol. kinda like someone who has lost their voice.
Outside bj loves to run around the yard. If you start playing with him be prepared for this little tank to run and jump, sometimes right into you. Loves rope toys and doing zoomies. I would not recommend cats, he isn't a cat lover. No small dogs or young children with him. He would run them over by accident. He's a solidly built bulldog and runs into you with an impact.

My perfect home for him would be a young, active couple with a patient man.  At first, bj will shy away from men and growl. He's afraid of them. With patience and understanding, he does come around, then He's all love and plays. Loves belly rubs.

He is UTD on vaccinations, microchipped, neutered, and ready to go!

animal.description:
Marvel is a 1.5 year old, male, 60 lb, American Staffordshire Terrier/American Bulldog mix. He is crate, house, and leash trained!
He is a very high energy boy who would love to be an only child and someone's running or jogging partner. He is great with everyone he meets and is such a cuddle bug. He loves jumping on the sofa with you to watch some tv but also loves a great game of fetch.
He loves all types of toys but b
all gives him life!

He's a dominate boy who needs a strong assertive owner to give him boundaries and limits. He would excel at any dog sport so being in any teams would be a plus! He
just completed some amazing training with Tail to Tail Training to give him a solid foundation and they are even willing to donate
a 1 to 2 hour refresher course to show an adopter what he's learned and how to handle him so he can reach his full potential. He isn't the biggest fan of other dogs only dogs that are submissive and lower energy.

His high prey drive that gives him an edge in dog sports makes him difficult to have around cats or small animals. That also makes him a bit of an escape artist if he chases a cat or squirrel up and over a fence. He's currently loving leashed walks for going potty and fetch out on leash with a long line/tether. Kids would need to be older and able to hold their own against his zoomies when he's excited.

If you are interested in adopting Marvel, please apply at
www.hhfrescue.org
.

The adoption fee includes vaccinations, bordetella, deworming, rabies, spay/neuter, microchip, a lifetime registration of the microchip, and sales tax. If adopting a puppy, the rabies and spay/neuter will be done at the same time by our vet once they are 4 months old and billed to us. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.

animal.description:
This is Chester, a 5 year old Poodle mix. He gets along well with other dogs, walks well on a leash and is crate trained.
He enjoys spending time outside. We believe he might have been and outside dog only.

Filling out an application is the first step in the adoption process. If you have questions, the best way to contact us is to email azdesertrottis@aol.com.
Thi
We don't always bring all animals to our adoption events so check ahead of time to make sure the animal you are interested in is still available. Some animals listed may already be promised.

Arizona Desert Rotti & Pals Rescue is a NO KILL rescue serving Tucson and the surrounding area. 

We do adopt out of area under the right circumstances. If you are willing to travel to Tucson to meet us, and to personally transport your adopted pet home, we may be willing to work with you. 

A home visit is usually required for the safety of our animals. We check the yard to make sure this little pup cannot escape, no predator can get in, and also look for hazardous plants. 

We do not adopt our dogs out unless you have a secured, fenced yard, it’s a requirement for the safety of the dog. At the end of the application, please include the type of fencing and the height of the fence you have around your yard. 

If you're interested in (DOG'S NAME) or any of our dogs, please fill out a pre application at: http://www.azdesertrotti.com/html/to_adopt.htm
Once you have filled out the pre-adoption application, someone will contact you about the dog to answer your questions and tell you where our Sunday adoption event is held.

Our dogs are bathed, dewormed, vet checked, given their required shots, spayed or neutered, and microchipped. 

Our rescues are homed with foster parents. They are fostered in homes so that we can tell you a little bit about their personalities, feeding schedule, habits, behavior, whether they get along with other dogs. We can tell you if they are crate trained, if they are leash trained and house trained. Most dogs need a refresher course on potty training when they go to a new home. They need to learn your routine, and it will be up to you to teach them. 

Even the most abused animals can be wonderful pets. It takes patience, love and good food, along with fun and commitment to the animal. Fosters work with these animals. They are a part of our families, while we are lucky enough to have them.
animal.name: Chester

Name: Toby
Breed: Heeler mix
Age: 1 year

I’M LOOKING FOR A JOB!! Are you a Heeler or herding/working dog type person?! Are you active and love to HIKE, run, or go for loooooong walks?! If you know my type of dog, you know how incredibly intelligent I am and ALWAYS looking to WORK!! I like to work, but I'm also said to be THE BEST cuddler out there! I am incredibly loyal and loving to the females in my home, but I am very weary of men. There's a high index of suspicion that I may have been abused, so I am in need of someone who will help work with me to get over my fear of men. I am set to go to a board and train program, but I need my next placement set up before I can go to training. I LOVE other dogs, but I'm not trustworthy with other small animals/creatures!   At this time, a home without kids is best.

Sooooo, what do you say.. we go for a long hike, spend a little time reinforcing my training and then go for a major cuddle session on the couch?! 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please fill out an application at survivortails.org or email adoptions@survivortails.org with any questions.

animal.description:
Foster Notes September 2017:

Overall Adonis was a great boy, he really is a sweetheart. He only needs minor work with house manners. After our evening walks, he would eat dinner and play a bit of fetch in the yard. We would all come back inside and he'd settle down nicely as we ate our dinner. We set up a baby gate to create boundaries during the day while our baby is walking around and playing. He would sleep in the house in a large crate in the hallway near our bedroom. My nephews (12 & 15) and sister in law came over to meet him on Tuesday, he was awesome. Very playful, gentle, friendly. I made him wait by the baby gate upon entrance, then by the door, on the side in a down/stay, when they left. He managed well, the treat helped :) No accidents in house. At meal time we put him in a down stay just a couple of feet away from dinner table, it takes a couple of tries, but then he stays. We have a neighbor that works in his yard, Adonis gave a couple of barks, when I called him he stopped and didn't bother again. We have another neighbor with a feisty boxer who stuck his nose under the fence, Adonis barked, then got into a playful position. I called him, he came over and left the dog alone. He did ok walking with me and the stroller. He was trying to keep up with the stroller, would bump it and stumble a bit, so I was working with him to stay near my side. He kept rubbing the gentle leader to try to get it off. I was working with him "don't rub" to leave it alone. Not sure if he did that with you guys. 
No other dogs in the home. 

He rode well in the rear compartment of the Ford Edge, no anxiety or whining , but about 10 minutes from the house he got excited and wanted to join us, so he tried to make his way over the back seat. He should probably ride in a carrier. We bathed him the day we got him at pet food express, he was perfect. I left him for an hour in the backyard when I went to the store, he was fine when I returned.

Adonis is a lover once he gets to know you - happy, eager and likes to give "hugs" to new friends. He is in need of puppy obedience classes and would excel due to his smart and attentive nature. Adonis walks well on leash and listens when you talk to him or ask him to sit. He travels well in a car and loves people. He likes dogs who match his play style & has good recall. Walks beautifully on leash with a gentle leader and will be a great companion to anyone looking for a pal. This handsome boy needs exercise, socialization with other dogs and a shep savvy home to love him!

animal.description:
PLEASE VISIT OUR WEBSITE AT WWW.PITRESCUE.ORG FOR INFORMATION ON OUR ORGANIZATION, ADOPTION POLICIES AND PROCESS, EDUCATIONAL INFORMATION, AND A FULL LIST OF OUR ADOPTABLE DOGS ALONG WITH PHOTOS AND FULL BIOS!!!
More pictures and info on this particular dog visit: https://www.pitrescue.org/victor

Apply online: http://fs22.formsite.com/siouxempire/form1/index.html?1316620486706

*Adoption application must be filled out with home visit and references (personal and vet) required prior to any adoption. Filling out an application does not obligate you to adopt, but merely begins the process. SEPR DOES adopt out of state!

Adoption fees: All SEPR adoptions are $300 for adults and $400 for puppies 1 year and under.  This includes: adoption fee (spay/neuter, utd vaccinations, micro-chipping), microchip registration, Gentle Leader, and two tie downs for use in your home. 

SEPR requires all adopted dogs attend a training class with their adoptive family within 90 days of their adoption. If an adoptive family completes this training class, they will be refunded $100 of their adoption fee with proof of licensed certificate. SEPR even offers an obedience class called Train-A-Bull to alumni over 1 year of age on a seasonal basis.  These classes are currently free!

*All other pets in the residence must be spayed or neutered and all pets up to date on vaccinations.

*SEPR requires all applicants must be 21 years of age.

*SEPR dogs are adopted to be inside the home, “part of the family” dogs only.

*Families with children 5 years of age and under wanting to adopt puppies will be reviewed on a case by case basis. Raising a puppy properly takes a lot of time, and we understand that in families with small children, time can be a limited commodity.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Update : Jesse is beginning to relax but seems to be more relaxed around women than men. Sudden movements startle him. If left alone he will approach people for treats and to be leashed but he is like a deer, the slightest movement might startle him so slow and steady is best.

Any potential adopters will have to meet him and work with him several times before he could be adopted and agree to follow the transition program to help Jesse settle in smoothly.

Jesse is a very sweet boy and has a very playful nature .......but his transition has to be slow so he can build up trust with his adopter. He will only be adopted to a home without children and with experience with under socialized German Shepherds .

UPDATE : JESSE is still very confused and will need additional time to decompress . He is beginning to take treats and takes them very gently.

Once he has become a bit more relaxed around us we will be able to introduce him .

He will need a quiet home, older kids or no kids since he has not lived with them, and adopters who have some familiarity with super shy dogs.

Jesse was very much loved but his human passed away unexpectedly and no one in the family could take him. Rather than take him to a shelter they reached out for rescue help and we were so happy we could take him.

Volunteers picked him up in NC and brought him here to MD . All who have met him say he is affectionate and warms up quickly.

Jesse is very sweet but understandably a little confused with all the changes in his life.

We will post updates soon and allow him time to decompress and relax in his new surroundings .

If you are not yet approved to adopt from All Shepherd Rescue, please fill out our online application at www.allshepherdrescue.com. Our adoption fee is $350.00.

animal.description:
Hi, are you looking for the most loyal, best buddy in the whole world?  And do have an enormous amount of patience?  If so, let me introduce you to Dodger.  He’s a 6-7 year old golden mix.  He has all the loving, loyal traits of a golden retriever- always happy to see you.  Never wants to leave your side, loves his toys, and is just a goofy, super loving boy.  He walks amazing well on a leash when he is by himself, but is not as good when his foster brothers come too!  He just gets so excited!  

He had a very rough past and unfortunately has some nuances that will probably never go away (hence the patience needed with him!). His one challenge is he is fecal incontinent.  He doesn’t seems to be able to feel it when he starts to “go” and once he starts, he can’t stop it.  His foster home keeps him on a strict diet to make sure his stool stays firm and easy to pick up, and he’s on a  pretty regular schedule, but you do need to stay outside with him while he goes.  

He will need to go to a home with another dog, as he take his  cues from other dogs.  He  would do best without cats or other fun small creatures to chase.   And he loves to roam certain rooms in the house- he is not a dog who can be crated

We require an application, phone interview and home visit prior to adoption. We will not discuss a specific dog with an applicant until the adoption process is completed. Our adoption fee for dogs under 8 months is $300, dogs between 9 months and 7 years is $250 and our super seniors are $125. Please visit our website for more information. Thank you!

animal.description: Skyee is a smart and playful young female who has been at our shelter for almost 10 months. A previous owner said Skyee had amazing house manners - house trained, no counter surfing, and only chewed on her toys. She likes rope and rubber toys and plays gently both by herself and with people. Skyee is also a big fan of splashing around in water, and knows sit, come, and shake. Skyee is loved by both staff and volunteers, who describe her as sweet and easy in the playyard. Skyee has a rough and rowdy play style with other dogs, but she has found a few doggy friends here at the shelter that she enjoys playing with. But Skyee needs a special home. Skyee gets really worked up on leash when she's passing people and dogs. She is insecure around people she doesn't know and needs a savvy owner with a low-traffic home to help her learn how to meet strangers and gain confidence and manners on leash. If you think you might be the right fit for Skyee, please schedule a virtual phone consultation to get more information on her. Check out my photos/videos!

animal.description:
Ollie's big, eyeliner-defined eyes will mesmerize you, watch out: he's just drawing you in for lots of belly rubs and petting! This young Pyr boy can't get enough loving from his humans, he loves children of all ages, and his knowledge of commands is sure to impress! Over the past few months, he's shown what a focused and quick learner he is. His foster mom has taught him a myriad of commands, from the basic "sit", "watch" and "down", to "drop it", "leave it" and "crate", and he responds to both verbal and some hand signals. His original owners reluctantly surrendered him because he had separation anxiety when they went back to work and although he's learning that people may leave for short periods of time and he will still be safe, his best home will be one where someone is home for the vast majority of the day. And if you have to go out, he understands "go for a ride"; just say "load up!" because he LOVES to ride in the car! This boy is gentle and respectful of children, fine with cats and other dogs (big and small), and loves playing with his dog friends. With new adults, he's a bit shy and needs a slower introduction by his owner. Being young, Ollie still has the puppy play drive - he plays with toys, including tug-of-war with his foster sister, and even the occasional fetch, but as a maturing teenager he will occasionally test the limits by nosing the counter or table for tidbits, or diving into the garbage can, and per his purebred pyr heritage, guarding his "flock". He is watchful over the children in the foster's home, stepping in when someone bigger plays rough with them, and tends to want to protect his foster mom more than dad on walks. He will require an owner with Pyr experience to guide him through his juvenile years, refine his serious guarding instincts, and a canine sister of similar size to play with and match his youthful energy. Ollie has shown himself to be an athletic climber, so will need a 6-ft. privacy fence with no support bars on the inside. He enjoys being outside and getting some zoomies in during the day, but mostly he prefers being inside with his people being a huge cuddle-bug :) 

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/rescue-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can call 877-739-3582 or email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Chief is an approximately 7-year-old American Bulldog mix with a gentle, submissive personality. He is around 80 lbs.  When Chief came to the rescue he was severely underweight and weak; his past is unknown. He was nursed back to health in foster care and gets along beautifully with the other dogs and people in the foster home.

 

 Chief has the most amazing loving eyes; when he looks at you with those kind brown eyes, it is almost impossible to resist the desire to love and take care of him. He is remarkably mellow and docile—happiest at the “back of the pack,” so to speak; when others are in control so he can just be himself. 

 

Although he has physically recovered, Chief still has anxiety which manifests outside (ie. whining, pulling, reactivity towards strange dogs). His foster mom has been working with a dog behaviorist. Chief has made excellent progress and enjoying his walks much more. 

Chief needs an experienced dog owner who can provide calmness and security, and is willing to complete training with the behaviorist if needed. Additionally, Chief needs a 30-minute daily walk, weekly new experiences, and continued socialization with other animals and people. He can live with other dogs and cats. Chief does well around his foster mom's small grandchildren, but simply due to his size, he would do best in a home without young children.

Chief is neutered, microchipped, and up to date in his vaccination. His adoption fee is $400

animal.description:
Sadie will be finished with her heartworm treatment on February 17, 2021.  She also rides well in a car.

Meet Sadie! She is a goofy, sweet Treeing Walker Coonhound. She’s approximately 3 years old and 60 pounds. 

Sadly, 2020 wasn't a good year for her either. She was diagnosed with heartworm disease and has been undergoing treatment for it. The treatment is a long, slow and painful process but luckily the heartworms are not spreadable to other animals. We are searching for a foster or foster-to-adopt home for her. 

Sadie has to be on strict exercise restriction to prevent any further problems as the heartworms slowly die. She needs a calm home where she can relax and go on leashed walks to potty while she heals from this disease. A home without cats is probably best as they excite her and cause her to show off that unique baying bark of hers. Luckily, she does great on leash and is easy to walk. She also is a huge foodie but she knows to “sit” and would love to learn more for treats. She just wants someone to love on her and not be alone through this treatment. 
If interested in making Sadie’s New Year's wish come true, please email us at humanecherokeecounty@gmail.com or call and leave a message at 918-457-7997.
If you can’t foster but would like to help with her treatment, we would be extremely grateful for donations as well. This treatment is very expensive and we couldn’t help these sweet animals without the help of our community. Donations can be mailed to HSCC P.O. Box 1354, Tahlequah, OK 74465 or you can do so through PayPal.

animal.description:
I AM IN FOSTER CARE! PLEASE FILL OUT OUR ADOPTION APPLICATION, ONCE PRE-APPROVED, GIVE US A CALL AND WE CAN SET UP AN APPOINTMENT FOR YOU TO MEET ME!

I am 27 lbs., 7 months old, and l am looking for my forever home. Toby is a special needs puppy due to a trauma that damaged the tail end of his spinal cord. Because of this, Toby does not have feeling in his hind end and tail and is incontinent.

Adoption Donation: $400

Note from his former foster: Toby is the best dog ever! Friendly, conversational, and cuddly! Toby loves taking walks but does not see much of the scenery because his nose never leaves the ground. He is learning to "sit" and "stay". At the end of the day, however, he will put himself to bed in his crate. He appreciates a cozy blanket or fleece and loves to snuggle with his dinosaur flannel. He loves to play tug-o-war with his spider, a rope, or stick and enjoys a good chew (but never once touched the furniture). He also likes other dogs. He loves to be outside in the sunshine and spent many days snoozing on our patio. 

All dogs are microchipped, neutered, current on all vaccines, heartworm tested and started on Tri Heart Plus; Vectra 3D.

All household members and any dogs from the household need to be present at the time of the adoption.

Our website is always kept 100% up to date with who is currently available.  As soon as animals are adopted, they are moved to the Adopted Pets page so if they are still listed on the Adoptable Dogs or Cats page, they are still available. So keep any eye on the site for any animals being added as available for adoption as new animals are added everyday! We would recommend if you haven’t done so already that you submit a general online adoption application with us so it is on file for when you are ready to come out and adopt. The adoption counselors will be able to show you many that would be a good fit for your family. Animal House Shelter can not guarantee breed or breed mix of our adoptable animals. The animals are posted on the website as a breed or breed mix based on their physical characteristics they most resemble. We also can not guarantee the ages of our adoptable animals or how large puppies will be when fully grown.

Please fill out an online adoption application. Visit our 'Adopt' page to view adoption process steps, policies, requirements and FAQ. View our 'Visit' page for hours and directions to our shelter. We look forward to seeing you soon!

animal.description:
This adorable Pyrenees mix boy is Tyson, a happy, fun and energetic young boy. He's likely a Pyrenees/Brittany Spaniel mix who is a smart fellow who learns quickly. He came into rescue with another female Pyrenees girl from a crowded shelter when they were nor reclaimed. We were able to get both dogs safe in the nick of time. Tyson is a good boy who will sit for treats and he takes direction well. He would be a great companion for leash walks and hikes as he is more energetic than the average full Pyr. He is also a nice size at 65 pounds. Tyson loves to play with toys and it's so fun to watch him throw a ball up in the air and try to catch it! He would do fine with a female companion or he would do well as an only dog. He does like to chase cats so a cat free home would be best. Tyson is a great dog - we just love him and so will you!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Roscoe is a 9-month-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, 4dx/heartworm tested, and neutered. This dog is also tested with other dogs, kennel-trained, and housebroken. We would love for you to meet this dog and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to Colorado's Safer At Home policies and to abide by social distancing protocols, we are HIGHLY encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. All adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically, should you want to proceed forward with the adoption. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions.***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Leo

DOB: 12/22/2019

Weight: 55 lbs

Adoption Fee: $375

I am a ten month old, 55lb mix. My foster mom's best guess is some blend of shepherd/lab. I am potty trained, behave well in the house, know basic commands, and walk well on a gentle leader. I came from Texas. I should not be in a family with kids or small critters, including cats. I have a strong prey drive and like to chase moving things. I love people, get along with other dogs with appropriate introductions, am very good in my kennel, enjoy car rides, and recently discovered I love the snow!

I am such a lover! I will get very excited to see you when you come home and will reach out for hugs and kisses while my entire body wiggles with joy! I love to follow my people around all over the house like a shadow. I would be best in a with not a lot of activity going on around the environment like dogs/people walking by. That would make me feel most safe. I love to play with other dogs, and luckily my golden retriever foster brothers have taught me a lot about how to read other dogs boundaries. I've grown leaps and bounds!

I think I lacked stimulation in my early life, so I made up my own games-chasing light and shadows. But my foster mom recognized this as not healthy and gives me treat balls, stimulating toys, plenty of exercise, and redirects me when I do this so that I learn to focus on other things. I am on medication to help my brain not get so worked up to begin with, and this has made me feel so much better! I'd rather snuggle now or play with my toys than chase lights.

I love people and despite not having a stable environment for the first 10 months of my life. I have a huge desire to trust, love and live life with so much joy! I almost always have a smile on my face and a wag in my tail. I am super smart and quick to learn how to please you. I can't wait to not have to worry about feeling safe and loved by giving someone who understands my needs my undying loyalty and love.

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal.

Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept.

******Elliott is blind and quite hard of hearing***** Elliot was given up because his family couldn't take him when they moved. He is a good boy and we feel bad for him. He would do best in a home with no stairs (inside or outside), one level living and a fenced yard. Because of his blindness, he can't/won't walk on a leash. Elliot does well in the big bed. He either sleeps on you or right up next to you but doesn't like to be disturbed! At home he likes to walk with his body up against your legs so he knows where you are and where he is going. He sometimes bumps into walls and goes into rooms and has a hard time getting out. You have to shake his dish and put it under his nose so he can find it. He likes other dogs but not cats. We prefer an all-adult home for Elliot with a small dog buddy his ager, a secure fenced yard and no cats or children. He will need a lot of patience as he settles in to his new home. It's not easy being an old blind nearly deaf dog and having to make changes. Won't you consider adding Elliott to your family?  Applicants must be willing to drive to Ellicott City, Maryland (10 miles south of Baltimore) to meet and adopt Elliott.****  Want to know more about Elliott - no fee for 60+ adopter? animal.description:
Est DOB: 09/2017
Current weight: 49 lbs
Alpha had a rough start to life - he and his brother Beta were found living behind a supermarket in North Katy. His finders brought the Alpha and Beta into the rescue and we were grateful to find out Alpha was heartworm negative!
Alpha is now neutered, microchipped, and up to date on all vaccination. While we don't know what happened to him before he was found, we do think he was previously abused as he is very nervous of strangers on first greeting. After he gets to know you, he opens up - he loves to give hugs, cuddle on the couch, and play ball. He's also a good running partner!
Due to his initial nervousness, Alpha did compete a 4 week board and train class where he learned all sorts of cool things like how to better handle meet and greets, sit, heel, and place. His training comes with free lifetime one on one sessions!
While Alpha enjoyed playing with Beta, he isn't as interested in other dogs and would be best as an only pet.
We are looking for an experienced dog owner that has the patience to let Alpha become comfortable with them - and be rewarded with an extremely loyal and loving dog. He would do best in a home with adults and no cats. While he would enjoy a yard, he would also do fine in an apartment setting as he likes to chill on the couch.
Please consider making this handsome boy a member of your family and contact us to arrange to meet him. More information about the adoption process and an adoption application can be found at https://almosthomepetrescue.org. An application form can be found on the website: https://almosthomepetrescue.org/apply-now-1 and is required to be approved for any meet and greet and adoption as Almost Home Pet Rescue is a foster based rescue.
$150 adoption fee covers spay/neuter surgery, heartworm test (in dogs over 6 months of age), core vaccinations, rabies vaccination, micro chip and registration, wormer, flea and heartworm prevention while the dog is in our care.

animal.description:
THIS IS A COURTESY POST PLEASE DO NOT CONTACT MASSPAWS.
 
Meet the Ace of Hearts! He’s a 5-year old, 45-pound mixed breed male located in Dover, NH. He is neutered and current on vaccinations. Though he’s always smiling, Ace experienced a difficult life and has been waiting in a shelter for months. 

Ace just wants a forever home where he’s your one and only. He needs someone willing to give him the life he deserves along with a little help to be a Super Ace!

If you enjoy the outdoors and keeping in shape, Ace would be a great match for you. He’s very active, loves exercise, and is always ready to go! He’d be a great running or hiking partner after a little help with his dog reactivity. A trainer is working with him now, but Ace’s adopter will be given tips on how to work with this fun-loving dog with just the right amount of goofiness. 

Ace loves playing with toys, but his favorite game is fetch. He also enjoys a game he calls ‘try to catch me!’ Ace would be great for agility training, too. After he’s worn out from playing, he will come to you for belly rubs and calming pats and rubs. He is an absolute love. 

Ace’s idea family is with committed active adults. Children should be 14 or older. He will be the only pet in the home. His ideal house is a single family with fenced yard. Ace is not suited to live in an apartment/ condo complex. 

Applications must be submitted online: https://popememorialcvhs.org/adoption-application/. Pope Memorial Humane Society is OPEN BY APPOINTMENT ONLY and has very limited staffing at this time. Applications will be reviewed as soon as possible. This can take up to one week. Please, no phone calls. If you have specific questions regarding Ace, please email adoption@popememorialcvhs.org Please tell them ARK sent you!!! #ARKforAce

Adoption Fee: $450
 Transport Fee: $160

Hank is a great pup. He would do wonderful in a home with no other pets. He gets along great with kids but it would be best if no small children were in the home. He loves playing and would be a wonderful hiking buddy. He is full of energy and needs someone who will exercise with him and take him for long walks. He likes to play with tennis balls and squeaky toys. He likes to snuggle on the couch too. 

Our adoption fee includes the spay/neuter, up to date vaccines, microchip, Interstate Health Certificate, and the transport service to get the new family pet to you. 

 Note: All dogs are located in foster homes in ALABAMA and will be transported NORTH AFTER ADOPTION. This means there is no way for a meet and greet before adoption. We try our best to give you honest personalities of the pup for you. We are more than happy to send videos, pictures, and even video chat so that you may have the connection with your pup before adoption. 

 COMPLETED APPLICATIONS TAKE PRECEDENCE OVER INQUIRIES! If you are interested in adopting, the FIRST step is to complete an application!

 Please be advised that our volunteers are busy rescuing, transporting, and caring for our animals. We will respond to your application as soon as possible. Upon review of your application, the rescue in Alabama will contact you, so you can ask any specific questions that you may have. 

 If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement.

 We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21.

animal.description: Hi there!  My name is Nicky (HWTH#18290B).  I am a Terrier mix, born on 9-9-09 and I weigh 14 lbs.  My owner moved away and didn’t take me with her so I came to Halfway to Home to find the forever home I deserve.  I am a low-maintenance boy in a cute package!  I am not terribly active so I only need a short walk or two a day to keep my joints healthy.  My lower jaw looks kind of funky which slows me down a bit while I am eating, but otherwise it doesn’t affect me at all.  My ideal home would be a quiet place without children with owners who like to cuddle. Condos or apartments are fine by me, but if you live on an upper floor you may need to carry me!   I am probably ok with other dogs, but it is important that we meet first to make sure we are compatible. I am not sure how I would do with cats.  Please don’t dismiss me because I am older.  Senior dogs are great companions because the most important thing to us is to be with owners who have a lot of love to give, and we will return it.  Thank you for reading about me, and if you would like more information or an appointment to meet me, please call Sandy at tele# 661-824-4495 (this is a land-line phone).

animal.description:
MEET NELLIE!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession.

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show. We have been told that you can go straight to the shelter and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog. From what we understand, the shelter will squeeze you in. (Please know this is not a guarantee). We hope your adoption process is smooth and full of happiness!

This amazing pup is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4480604.

When Nellie first came to the shelter, she was very scared and timid and didn't understand why she was there. She was very wary of the kennel staff and didn't want to interact with them. The kennel staff kept working with her and she is doing so much better. She is easy to leash in her kennel and walks out to the play yard without any issues. Her last time out of the kennel, she was playful and bouncy walking to the play yard. She was calm, wanted to be petted and the staff found out that she knows sit, shake and down for treats. She walked back to her kennel with ease. She just needed some time to understand that the staff was there to help her and take care of her.

When Nellie was in the play yard with other dogs, she was tolerant of the dogs and she enjoyed laying in the shade with another timid dog. Nellie needs an adopter that understands her start at the shelter and that she's nervous when she meets new people, but once she gets to know you, she'll be ready to show you the tricks that she knows. Just make sure you have some treats. If you already have a dog at home, bring them with you to meet Nellie! Come and meet her today!

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

Otis is a handsome 2-year-old Double Merle Great Dane who is DEAF and ready to find his forever family. He is an alpha male and will need an experienced Dane owner. Otis is good with medium and large dogs with proper introductions. He knows basic commands and is house and crate trained. He absolutely loves his people, but NO children under 12 in his forever home. Otis is a sweet velcro Dane that is always ready for his belly scratches. He is fully vetted, microchipped, neutered and vaccinated.

We will require Otis to be in training within 30 days of adoption. Basic Obedience Training is a crucial opportunity for Otis to bond with his new family, learn new commands and reinforce good manners.

For more information about our adoption process and an application please visit www.whitekissesgreatdanerescue.com/adopt

animal.description:
**Click on the link https://www.patreon.com/AlmostHome to Become a Patron! For only $5 a month you can read wonderful stories about the animals who have come through our program. everything from how we got started to cruelty and rehabilitation cases. This money goes directly to caring for the animals in our program as well as helps save others desperately needing rescue. Thank you in advance - we seriously could not do what we do without your support. 

**IMPORTANT!!  Please read the entire bio before contacting us with questions. Send us an email requesting an application to start the adoption process adopt@almosthomenm.org   Make sure you add our address to your safe sender list or watch your junk/spam emails.  For more photos please visit our Facebook page.   http://www.facebook.com/pages/Almost-Home-New-Mexico/203840136304815 

Approximate DOB 5/26/2012

Size - Small about 6 lbs maybe

History- Surrendered to rescue due to medical issues and inability to care for her.

Temperament- Very, very sweet- possibly one of the best temperaments ever. She is so loving and very well behaved.

Energy Level- Very active - but will pretty much do whatever you are doing. If you are in the yard she is with you- and every so often gets the zoomies and runs super fast around you. If you are on the sofa relaxing though she is good with that as well. She is just perfect.

Dogs/Cats- She is good with everyone here.

Housetrained- She is so smart- completely house trained. Doesn't give me an indication I just put everyone out every few hours.

Chica is an amazingly perfect little girl. She will be a wonderful addition to any family wanting a perfect little dog to love and cuddle with.  She is a perfect little girl. She did recently have a dental and lost several teeth so should be on small kibble or raw.

Adoption fee $250 includes spay, dental, age appropriate vaccinations (4 for puppies), deworming, microchip, rabies, collar and leash, training information, and all the support you need. 

Send us an e-mail to adopt@almosthomenm.org requesting an application to adopt this sweetie!! Animals are seen by appointment only. An application must be submitted to us prior to making an appointment. We do give a discount when adopting multiple pets.

If you would like to donate to our cause and help care for the animals in our care please visit our main website www.almosthomenm.org and click on the donate button at the top left of the screen..

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Loki is a very handsome little 1 year-old Cattle Dog with beautiful markings. He was surrendered to a county dog shelter by his owner because of his high prey drive--chasing cats and chickens. Loki has done well with other dogs in his foster home, but will try to herd them which is true to his breed. Loki needs an active person or mature family who'll give him a job to do every day. He would make an excellent trail buddy once he gains a little more experience on the leash. Loki has done well with crate-training in his foster home and should be able to pick up the house rules quickly in his new home. He would not do well left alone for long workdays and needs a big fenced yard (aboveground fence only--no invisible fence) to play in along with a canine buddy to pal around with. Loki is a very smart dog who picks up new routines quickly. He loved having his photos taken and made great eye contact with the camera. In addition to plenty of physical exercise each day, Loki needs lots of mental stimulation as well to keep him sharp and engaged. If you're an experienced Cattle Dog person looking for your next buddy, Loki might be the dog for you. Loki was adopted from us shortly after he arrived here but was returned after several weeks because he became very protective of his home and family. He was not welcoming of visitors to the home and exhibited leash reactivity with other dogs when on walks in the neighborhood. He needs a quiet home in a more rural area without close neighbors and few visitors. He becomes very attached to his people and isn't able to handle busy urban or suburban environments. Loki weighs about 28 pounds and his adoption fee is $325. He's neutered, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Loki. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Loki and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

Meet Scooby!  This stunning male Bluetick Coonhound came to our rescue from a all the way from Tennessee.  He was rescued from difficult conditions where was not being well cared for on the property of a man breeding hounds.  He deserves a better life with a family to love and care him.  Scooby is friendly and sweet.  He loves treats and takes them very gently.  He enjoys going for walks and being outdoors where he can use his hound nose! 

The NAWS Dog Adoption Program operates as a rescue versus a shelter.  We believe in matching the right dog with the appropriate family based on each specific dog or family's needs.  To achieve this, we believe in spending the appropriate amount of time with each family to allow for enough interaction time with potential adopters.  This cannot be achieved if people stop by unexpectedly to meet our dogs.  Please e-mail Stacy at stacy@nawsus.org to setup a day or time to meet with one of our Dog Adoption Counselors and our potential adoptees.  Thank you!

animal.description:
Hi there my name is Louie and I'm a 10-month pitbull mix. I'm from Franklin County Animal Shelter and am at HALO though the Shelter & Rescue Partner Program. The shelter thought I would be a good candidate for this program because when I was surrendered to the shelter, I was very fearful and showing fear agression (growling at the shelter staff). At HALO, I learned that people are not scary and are actually very nice. I also have many, many dog friends who have helped me overcome my fear of people. I am currenlty working on: walkling nicely on a leash (I am still afraid of bikes), respecting items in my room (I still chew on things I shouldn't), and greeting people properly (sometimes I bark at them). Even though I am a work in progress, I am the sweetest boy with the cutest personality. I would do best in a home with someone who has another confident, well adjusted dog who can teach me how to overcome my issues. I've only been at HALO since August and have made amazing strides. The people at HALO are confident that I will be a perfect companion given the chance. Love, Lou-Lou 

We are a foster based organization and DO NOT have our adoptable pets at HALO. You must complete an adoption application to meet the cat or dog. We are by appointment ONLY. If you are interested in adopting Louie, please submit your application www.halok9behavior.com/forms or Franklin County Animal Shelter at dogs.franklincountyohio.gov/services/adoption

animal.description:
Nash is a special 'rescue only' dog who has bite experiences. He will not be available until we have been able to work with him and feel comfortable in him meeting experienced adults. This posting is FYI only - He is 3 years young and 55 lbs.
NO APPOINTMENTS at this time. Applications only from adults experienced with big dog training. NO APPOINTMENTS at this time. No children, no cats, no other dogs. He did get along well with Marverick here, who was 20 pounds bigger than Nash.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

FAST FACTS:
*4 Years Old - 56 Pounds
*Generally Laid-Back But Has Bursts of Playful Energy
*Dog Friendly - Best With Submissive Dogs
*No Cats
*Older Children
*Potty/Crate Trained
*Training Required 

BIO:
Greetings! My name’s Dorothy, and I’m a beautiful American Staffordshire Terrier who is available for adoption through Fetching Tails Foundation. In general, I’m pretty laid back and like to keep my energy levels low. I'm a big cuddler and tend to go with the flow, but I do make exceptions for some Olympic-style backyard zoomies and high-octane play sessions with my toys. This excitement can carry over into first introductions with other dogs. It takes me a few minutes to chill, but I will eventually get there. While I’m working on making better first impressions with other four-legged friends, I think that I would be happy with another submissive canine pal or in an only-dog household. Though, it’d be best that my forever home be feline-free because I can’t imagine cats would have time for my silly antics. With that said, I get along very well with every human that I meet. I love snuggling and spending time with my people!

I’ve accomplished so much already - including crate and potty training - and I contentedly sleep in my crate when left alone for anywhere between 3-8 hours at a time. Being the strong girl that I am, I could use some more practice with my leash manners. I’m incredibly smart, so it’s nothing a little training and patience couldn’t help! Someone once said that there’s no place like home, and I cannot wait to experience that feeling for myself. If I had a pair of ruby slippers, I’d click my paws together right now and wish to find my forever home today! 

Cheers,
Dorothy

animal.description:
FAST FACTS:
*2 Years Old - 85 Pounds
*Medium Energy: Active/Energetic Outside, Calm in Home
*No Dogs
*No Cats
*Fenced Yard Required (Tall Privacy Fence Preferred)
*Experienced Owners - He is Very Strong on Leash
*Quiet Suburban Neighborhood Preferred
*Potty Trained & Crate Trained
*Training Required

BIO:
Ciao! My name is Dante and I'm on the search for a comfy couch and fun-loving family! I am the kind of dude who will match the energy of my family: my favorite activity in the world is lounging on the couch, but a close second is playing outside. If you want to relax all day with some Netflix, let's do it! If you wanna romp around and run zoomies in our yard, I am all about that life! When I want to play, I can be quite boisterous so I would do best in a home without young children; teenagers who can handle my size and energy would be fine. I should be your only pet for now (no other dogs or cats, please!) I like other dogs but I get overexcited and my enthusiasm turns off a lot of potential friends, so until I learn better manners and work on my introductions I would do better as the only dog in my home. I also need a fenced yard (tall fences that are at least 5 feet, please!) so I can run zoomies and play fetch before we curl up on the couch again to catch some zzzz's.

I am a very smart guy, and generally well behaved around the home. I am potty and crate trained: I actually love my crate and think of it as my personal man cave where I can enjoy some quiet time chewing on durable toys and kongs. Everyone is a work in progress, however, and I would appreciate a family with previous strong-dog experience who will work with me on my leash manners. I get SO excited when I see new people or dogs and can pull hard to greet them. I would do best in a quiet suburban neighborhood where there are not many distractions on walks, and my humans need to commit to training classes so I can work on not pulling so hard on the leash when I want to try and meet new potential friends. I already know a few basic commands such as sit and wait, and I really enjoy learning so I think training classes could be the first of many fun adventures! I am a big, goofy guy who doesn't realize just how big I am, but big dogs have big hearts filled with lots of love, am I right? I hope you fill out an adoption application soon so I can show you how affectionate I can be!

Love,
Dante
