animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.BONDED WITH MUFFY
Fate brought Muffy and Barbie together in the same foster home and now they are besties! Their destiny is leaving for their forever home as a bonded pair. These two start playing the minute their eyes open in the morning and they will continue until bedtime if allowed. These two love to do
almost
everything together including galloping in and out side-by-side for potty breaks, patrolling the property, and digging holes in the yard. Barbie is a hilarious goof ball and very expressive! She is coming up on her 1-year birthday in January. She has an assertive play-style that includes lots of growly noises but it's all good natured. Barbie has a strong Pyr paw and runs like a rocket, so would not do well in a house with small children. Typical of most female Pyrs Barbie is independent and strong-willed (and typical of some teens, a little demanding) so she will need Pyrents who are strong and fair leaders and willing to work with her and provide consistent boundaries. Barbie has a jaw deformity due to possible trauma or birth deformity but she has no problems drinking and eating. Barbie continues to learn it's okay to ride in the car and is crated trained although not a big fan. Barbie does NOT like sharing food or treats with Muffy so they need to be separated while eating. Barbie is still learning there is plenty of water for everyone so may need to be redirected while Muffy is drinking. Barbie is currently being fostered in Tacoma, WA.

OUR REQUIREMENTS FOR PUPPY ADOPTION:

1) PUPPIES WILL ONLY BE PLACED IN HOMES THAT HAVE AT LEAST ONE MEDIUM TO LARGE YOUTHFUL, PLAYFUL RESIDENT DOG that is age 1 or older. This helps integrate the dog into your household easier by giving the pup a mentor.

2) These puppies are not livestock dogs. They must be family pets that are allowed inside the home.

3) In addition to the youthful playful dog, someone must also be home at least part of the day. Please do not apply for a puppy if you are gone 8+ hours a day.

4) We give preference to applicants with prior Great Pyrenees knowledge/experience.

5) Secure and visible fencing required.

6) You must have a plan in place to socialize your puppy properly.

7) Please do NOT write us and ask if this puppy is available. If it is posted, it is available. However, we may be working other applications that came in before yours. If so, by the time you are approved, the puppy may not be available.

Adoption Fee: $425

All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, heartworm tested and up to date on vaccinations.

Transport Fee: $300

Transport fee includes the cost of transport plus the Health Certificate required for USDA approved transport.

All of our dogs are spayed/neutered and up to date on vaccinations.

Adoption applications can be found on our website: www.greatpyrsandpaws.org

https://greatpyrsandpaws.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=5959

Northwest adopter pays cost of transport to independent transport company. Transport is arranged by GPPR.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Tonka is a sweet 2-year-old, 50-pound Pitbull looking for a family who will help to excavate his trust and pile drive him with love.

Tonka may be built like a bulldozer, but he has a gentle and calm spirit. This boy loves nothing more than to front load into your lap for snuggle time. Like a crane operator, he will carefully pick out treats from your hand, puzzles games or a snuffle mat. And even a flatbed truck full of toys or bones is not enough for this guy as he is happy to sample any toys or bones that are on the lot. Tonka will demolish dirt piles that make a monster truck look like child's play and rev himself up for a good round of wrestling with other pups.

Tonka has previously tested positive for Heartworm (which is not contagious to other canines) and has completed his treatment. He has been hovering around the home, like a helicopter, with minimal exercise, so he will need to slowly ramp up activity. The Rescue Crew will paint the lines to guide you to success by providing a mentor and vetting coordinator to assist you through his transition.

Tonka does well with other dogs in the home. Another dog in the home would help grade the way and provide some confidence. However, he would also do just fine paving the route himself into the home as an only animal. Tonka has not yet been around cats or children, so we are unsure how that team would work out.

Tonka is a sweet and gentle boy, built like a Tonka truck but with a heart that will pave the way for him to be a breed ambassador for Pitties everywhere. Tonka's life may be under construction, but he can't wait for the day when his forever family is unveiled to him.

The adoption fee covers the cost of the animal's spay/neuter surgery, microchipping, FIV/FeLK testing (for cats) or Heartworm Testing (for dogs), deworming and all core age appropriate vaccinations. For the most complete information regarding this animal, and all of our adoptable pets, please ensure you are visiting our website directly at www.RescueCrew.org. You can also access the necessary online adoption application here as well. Thank you.

animal.description:
Lollipop is approximately 2 years (Born December 2018).  He’s in great health. Guessing weight at about 15 to 20 pounds. He is a great little dog once accustomed to his environment. He  gets along fine with other dogs, but because if his lineage would not recommend a home with small children.

Lollipop Blue is a border collie mix (potentially chihuahua father) with a big heart and playful demeanor. As he has not been socialized, he will be shy with new people and may take a little time to warm up, especially if there are multiple people around. Despite this, he is very gentle and loves to be held. Luckily he’s small enough to sit in your lap or cuddle on the couch while you pet his head and scratch behind his ears. Because he has spent a lot of time outside, he is not yet potty trained but he is doing well in a crate and can hold his bladder until it’s time for a break. Blue has displayed some separation anxiety tendencies and likes to stay close to his people to feel safe. Otherwise, he is content to lay in his bed or in a soft place near you while you work. While new to playing fetch with others, he loves to amuse himself with a soft toy that he can flip up and throw around. He is nervous with new sounds so a quiet home would be ideal, although he loves other dogs and would not mind sharing with some more friends. Because of his breed, he has light herding tendencies but quickly corrects and understands “No”. For this reason he may not be good in a home with young kids. Just like he enjoys quiet, Blue is also very quiet and does not bark or cry. He has a medium-low activity level and does good with a few short walks each day, but has sturdy legs and energy for more if you’re up to it. He is good to match your energy level and happy to lay around so long as he can check in on you and have a quiet place to relax. When he wants attention he will come up to your side and might gently place his paws on you, but is good about not jumping and understands “No” and “Down”. If you don’t have time to play, he will either lay down or play with his toys on his own. He is the perfect work-from-home buddy. We’re still working on other basics like “Sit” and “Stay”, but he’s smart and will quickly pick up a routine and training.
animal.name: Lollipop Blue

animal.description:
I’m Dexter… I can’t see you too well or hear you much, but I am still a really good senior boy with time on my hands … paws … whatever you want to call them, I would just like to spend with you.

I know I’m not a JRT, but Mama Donna was at animal control to pick up someone else and one of the volunteers said, “Please, take this boy. It’s his last day.” And it was! It was my last day in the scary place, and the next day I began a new chapter at the ranch. Now I’m ready to write the book with you.

I am a Maltese mix around 9 lbs. and I am fine with being picked up and held. I just had all my vetting done and am ready for a quiet home with a well-fenced yard where I can share my life with people who understand there is still plenty of joy in this Golden Boy.

I have some chronic trouble with my eyes.  I was so neglected for so long that my corneas are all scratched up.  I have dry eye and glaucoma.  But all that is being treated and I am not in pain.

I had a dental and am UTD on my vet stuff.  I sure would like a lap.  

Come see me at

http://www.jackrusselladoptions.org/

animal.description:
Sweet Sweet Mia comes to us from Tijuana Mexico.  She was found tied up to a bridge, skin & bones, and appears to have been spending her entire life like this, as her rescuers had to talk the man holding her under the bridge, into giving her up.  She is approx 1 year old

Mia is Deaf, so she will need a special someone to take her in, and work with her.  She is not doing well in our current crazy rescue environment, as she can't keep up with all the Chaos.  She is a very sweet dog with people, tolerant of some younger dogs, but really needs someone to be one-on-one with her.  A controlled environment is a MUST for her, and having someone she can trust is another.  She will need full training, as we just got her in.  Adoption fee is negotiable, as we do know training is needed, and we can help find a trainer if needed.

Mia is an active dog. We have been working on lead training her, but without verbal direction, it takes more time than our short staffed rescue can handle right now.  We are hoping that this one special person(s) is out that there that can handle this little girl and get her on the right track.  Are you that one special person?
animal.name: Mia

animal.description:
Javi is a 2-3 years old, male pitbull. Like so many dogs in Texas, Javi wandered onto a woman's property. He was not chipped and no one came looking for him. The woman reached out to us and we were able to get him neutered and up to date on his vaccinations. Javi has spent a lot of time outside. He LOVES people and spent time with a young child where he was giving them kisses. We have not been able to observe him for long periods of time with children, so we can't say for certain how he would act. While at the foster's house there was a scuffle with her little dog which ended with that dog having a swollen lip. We are not certain the details of the scuffle and do not know if Javi was the aggressor or not. Due to this incident, we are recommending a home with no dogs and no cats. Javi is currently in boarding and the staff comment often how sweet he is. We would love to find him a home who can be patient and provide him the love he deserves. 
 Javi is in a foster home in the Kent, WA area. He LOVES people and would love to find his forever home. 

Please fill out an application 
https://heartoftheunderdog.org/adoption-application

I am looking for my home that will enable my final transformation into a couch potato. As a ten year old Golden Girl, I identify closely with Rose, as I always want pets and love. I would ask that my forever family understand that I like to express what is on my mind a lot. From grunts, groans, to barks, I have a lot to say! I can't wait to meet you!

He loves romping around in the backyard with his brother, Pedro. Pablo is seeking an active family as he loves to explore!  Pablo is an energetic pup with a great sense of adventure. This pair was surrendered by their previous owner to local animal control. Willene, founder of STARS was contacted by animal control and these brothers were taken in to safety. Now, STARS is hoping to find them their furever homes.

Our adoption fee is $500. This includes spay/neuter, microchipping, deworming, and all age-appropriate vaccinations.

animal.description:
Please click "MORE ABOUT US" at the right and read about our adoption process before contacting B.O.N.E.S.



5.5 year old male
**Needs a Physically Fenced Yard**
Good with dogs
Unsure about cats
Good with older children

Hi there, I'm Jake. I am a big time snuggler. My preference is to cuddle with a human, but a stuffed toy is a good substitute when needed. I do like to be the center of attention, but who can blame me? I just love playing and interacting with my people.

Of course, in addition to enjoying the company of humans, I adore the companionship of other canines. I will do best in a home with a submissive sibling. If you don't already have one in your family, may I suggest Kooter? He and I are already very good friends.

If you adopt me, you will be getting some perks. For example, I am already house trained, which I know you like. I also respond to the commands "sit," "stay," and "come." If I do something of which my foster parents do not approve, they will use a stern voice to let me know. When that happens, I respond very well because I want to always make my humans happy.

Do you drive? I hope so because I just love going for car rides. I sit nicely clipped in the back seat and take in all the sights and smells. Of course, I am equally as happy spending most of my days lounging around or playing.

At night, when I curl up in bed with my foster family, I dream of finding a family of my very own. I know my furever home is out there. I sure do hope we find each other soon. Just think, we can keep each other warm as the cooler weather moves in. What a cozy winter we will have together.



------

B.O.N.E.S. is a foster-home-based rescue organization serving dogs and potential adopters in the New England states. We do not have a shelter. Please visit our home page at www.bonesbeagles.org for information about our adoption process.

Of course, if the car stops for too long, I bark: "let's go, let's go, I want to move!" Walking on my leash is also something I enjoy doing with my foster parents. I walk very nicely so that humans and canines all have a pleasant time.

When the sun is shining, you will most likely find me sun bathing. Ahhh, what a wonderful, warm feeling. Would you mind handing me the suntan lotion?

I will do best in a home with another dog since I do value canine companionship. If you do not already have one, may I suggest Jake? He's my very good buddy.

If you are hoping to add a loving, snuggly, sun-worshiping, furry family member to your home, please consider adopting me. It would really be a dream come true to have a furever home. Looking forward to meeting you soon.

Queenie is able to use a dog door to go outside but if it is dark(early morning, late at night) she may not make it through the door. She has a hard time with depth perception. I leave pee pads by the dog door & she knows to use it if she can’t make it out side.  Queenie loves to go on walks & sniff all the wonderful smells. She loves attention & when happy will rub her back on the floor. She is not a big barker unless others are barking. Queenie is a very gentle senior lady hoping to find the perfect companion to spend her retirement. Great on the leash, she enjoys long, quiet walks with ample time to smell the roses. Quick to learn the doggie door leads to sunbathing on the patio furniture, she sure is a creature of comfort.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting, please apply directly with bigdogrescueproject.org/adopt.

Available for adoption in WA, OR, ID, CA, or Vancouver, BC. Currently fostered in Tacoma, WA. 

Please read Brienne’s whole bio!

Brienne is about 3 years old. She weighs about 80-85 pounds and is a big, strong girl!

This girl loves to love her person! She will be a wonderful companion for a single person or couple, preferably female, who live a quiet, private lifestyle. Her ideal day would be roaming her yard, destuffing some toys, and then taking a long nap in the company of her favorite person. 

Brienne is dog reactive and stranger reactive. She has significant prey drive and is not well suited for a home where she would have access to or interactions with other animals. She finds strangers very stressful. She can manage viewing strangers from afar (Like on a walk) but a busy household with people coming in and out of the house would be difficult for her. 

Homes with other animals (dogs, cats, birds, rabbits, chickens, livestock, etc) will NOT be considered. Homes with children under 15 in the home or regularly visiting the home will NOT be considered. 

Brienne is muzzle trained, crate trained, and potty trained. Her leash skills are good but not perfect. The muzzle she uses will come home with her and we are happy to walk any adopters through the “how and why” of her muzzle. Her muzzle is an important tool to keep her and others safe while training her and expanding her world!

Brienne loves her crate and is accustomed to sleeping, eating, and relaxing in there. We highly recommend any adopter continues this practice. 

Brienne would be well-suited to a home with a well-fenced, large yard. She loves to go out and patrol her yard, searching for excellent smells. 

She is not a dog that would do well in dog parks or daycare. She thrives on a quiet, routine, homebody life!

Brienne currently takes daily Prozac to help mitigate her stress and anxiety. She also uses CBD oil and composure treats as needed. These are all great tools for helping her feel more safe and confident. 
 
We anticipate that Brienne’s new family will set up several meet and greets with her before starting a slow transition into her new home. 

Adopters should be prepared to work with a vet, trainer, and/or behaviorist to give Brienne the opportunity to put her best paw forward!

We are so excited for Brienne to have a chance to be her best self!

Our adoption fee includes age appropriate vaccinations, deworming, microchipping and transport expenses. Adoption fee for Brienne is  $150 to help offset travel and medical expenses.

Applications can be made at bigdogrescueproject.org/adopt

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Brienne is not a match for homes with other animals, including birds, chickens, livestock, etc.

animal.description:
IN VERMONT

Meet Cedric! More pictures and video to come!

Cedric is 8 months old (approx. DOB 2-15-20), male, 35 lbs., vetted, is or will be neutered, and micro-chipped. We used this picture to post because this is Cedric right now. He is a broken soul that needs a very special home. He is shut down, scared to even move. He has shown some glimmers of progress but quickly resorts to hiding and being invisible.

He is a flight risk; he will try to flee if he thinks he can. This is Cedric. We know he will heal; but it will be on his own clock and in his own comfort zone. His very special home will have patience and empathy to let him just "be" until he is ready.

His ideal home will be knowledgeable about fearful dog and will work with our Team on how to help him. Also he will need another dog or dogs around that he can look to for observing trust with humans. We do not know what happened to this poor pup; we don't want to even imagine but we do know our Community will help him; because he is worth it. He has had some sort of emotional trauma. That's why we saved him! Stay tuned for more information as Cedric is a new rescue!

If you are interested in adopting Cedric please fill out an Application at

www.Passion-4-Paws.org

(please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out his Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

Maltby is in a foster home, and is currently not at the shelter. Please find info below on how to adopt him, thanks.



Meet Maltby! He's a gentle giant with a sensitive soul and he would love to shake your hand. When he came to the shelter he was very shy at first, but with time he has opened up and showed us his playful side. He loves catching treats mid-air and romping around when excited. His sweet gaze will melt your heart. We don't know exactly how old Maltby is as he came to us as a stray but we think around three years old. 



He would prefer to be the only dog in the house. He can get spooked by sudden movements or loud noises, so we think a home with adults only or older children would be best. His ideal environment would be a house with a large fully fenced yard on a quiet neighborhood street with little to no foot traffic. A busy apartment complex contains too many surprises and other furry friends!



HOW TO ADOPT - Please fill out a Dog Adoption Application, available at http://www.seattle.gov/animalshelter/forms.htm and email it to the Seattle Animal Shelter Foster Dog Program at adoptionreview@gmail.com.



IMPORTANT NOTE: Many of our dogs will receive numerous applications, and the Seattle Animal Shelter asks for your patience during the process of finding the very best match. If you have questions about this dog that have not been answered above, please contact us at sasfosterdogs@gmail.com. If you would like to arrange to meet this dog, you must submit an adoption application. Thank you!

animal.description:
NOTE: During the 2020-21 winter holidays, we are updating our webpage and moving the profiles of adoptable Pyrs to www.carolinapyrrescue.com. Esme is typical of the kind of wonderful dog we have available! We always have 15-20 Pyrs looking for furever homes, and we welcome those interested in adopting a Pyr to read our policies and fill out an application at carolinapyrrescue.com. This application is generic and to come meet the Pyrs. Those who find their match can fill out the adoption contract once they meet the right dog. We will have updated profiles featured under the OUR PYRS tab at carolinapyrrescue.com, but as our volunteers rebuild our webpage, other volunteers are continuing to place dogs, and welcome those who want to adopt to fill out an application. The miracle of rescue is that the right dog is at the rescue for the right people at the right time!

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Esme, short for Esmerelda, came to us as an owner surrender.  

She is three years old.

Esme is spayed and fully vaccinated. She is heart worm negative.

We truly wish Esme wasn’t in rescue. Her owner reached out to us early in 2020 when she was diagnosed with terminal cancer. She passed with her beloved dogs, and then friends of her and volunteers got Esme and her siblings, Solomon and Oliver, to rescue. Some folks think rescue dogs always come to us with histories of abuse or neglect. Esme was very, very loved by his first owner and her family and friends.  

We know all about Esme’s Pyrsonality. She is a confident and social female Pyr who help her brothers in line. She is social with humans large and small and affectionate. 

Esme is also playful and would enjoy sharing a home with a playful male dog her size or smaller dogs of either sex. She can be adopted with Solomon if folks are looking for a bonded pair. She can’t share a home with another female dog her size. 

She could join a home with children, but for now she is best matched with older children only because she jumps. We are working on that. She could go to experienced dog owners who have small children if they understand how to correct that behavior and commit to working on it. She loved the little ones who helped care for her first owner at the end of her life, but she's still learning how to keep all "four on the floor" when she's excited. 

We don’t know if she is tolerant of cats. We don’t have cats at the rescue and can’t test her.

Like all Pyrs, Esme needs a solid and securely fenced yard. 

Those interested in adopting a Pyr should read our policies and fill out an application to meet the Pyrs at carolinapyrrescue.com.

Ghost has yet to meet a stranger, loves exploring new scents on his walks, and is the best cuddle bug you will find. He is house trained, and is a perfect gentleman when left on his own in the house!

He is currently the only pet in his foster mom's house. He does get along with calm dogs after a slow introduction and mostly ignores cats and is easily redirected. Loveable, quiet and easy going companion looking for his forever home.

animal.description:
Meet Lisa! A blue and white beautiful pitbull looking for her furever home. She originally had a rough start to life and was extremely emaciated to where every bone could be seen, since he has learned all the good things people have to offer. Lisa is a
extremely smart lady as she has learned "sit," "stay," "break" (from the stay), and "drop it" (which includes off-limits objects as well as dropping the toy during fetch). Lisa LOVES a fun, energy filled game of fetch. Even when playing in the dark, Lisa will sniff around methodically until she finds the object if she loses sight of where it was thrown. She would be a great candidate for someone interested in doing nose work with their furry companion. At the age of 3 years Lisa has already mastered crate and house training. Though Lisa does have basic training she would benefit from having a experienced owner who can continue working on her training as she does become nervous of new people, though has been overcoming this
marvelously
with structure and routine. A family with teens-and-up and no small dogs would be a great match for Lisa. During her down time Lisa enjoys lounging on the couch or the bed and snuggling up with her human. She also LOVES chew toys. Lisa is just a wonderful dog and will be a fun addition to her new home! Send in your adoption application today;
https://www.underhoundrailroad.org/adoption/

Lisa is currently being fostered in South Carolina, please reach out to us for when she is expected to travel to Maine.

animal.description:
DOB: 9/21/12
Jericho has been described by our volunteers as a "happy go lucky gentle giant". Jericho will need a bit of extra attention as this sweet boy is deaf. He is very easy going and chill with a happy and loving personality! He loves chasing balls in the yard and going for walks (he will need a little training on not pulling while leash walking), car rides, doggy play groups, and enjoys doing some agility work as well! Although he was found as a stray it's clear that this boy grew up in a home! He loves treats so training sessions are favorite. Jericho will do best with a patient, dog savvy adopter who is willing to learn the best ways to communicate with this handsome boy, plus the guidance and help from Canine Company who is donating (3) eManners/Obedience training sessions to his adopter.. Call the shelter to make an appointment to meet him!  


Jericho is up to date on vaccinations, is micro-chipped, and is Neutered. 
Adoption fee: Jericho's adoption fee has been paid for by a ROAR friend!!
Canine Company is donating (3) eManners/ Obedience training sessions to his adopter. 


**For more information regarding ROAR’s adoption policies and procedures, please visit our website at roar-ridgefield.org and select the ‘adopt’ tab on the home page. ROAR does not accept online applications. All applications must be filled out at the shelter.

animal.description:
Piper came from a breeding facility and due to lack of early socialization has struggled to bond with humans.  He has made great improvements in his foster home in the last couple months and we feel he is ready to join a permanent family if you have experience and the patience and desire to work with a breeder released dog (with trust issues ).  He will require a home with another playful dog ( sheltie preferably), sufficient time at home during the day ( not a long day of crating). We will not be placing him in a home with children and will only choose an age appropriate adopter (he is only one year of age ).  A SECURELY FENCED YARD IS MANDATORY.  He loves to run like the wind when he plays outdoors.  He has also begun to be a couch/recliner snoozer which has helped with his human bonding process. 

BEFORE INQUIRING ABOUT ADOPTING ONE OF OUR AVAILABLE PETS or TAKING THE TIME TO FILL OUT OUR QUITE DETAILED APPLICATION, PLEASE REVIEW THE INFORMATION PROVIDED ON OUR ADOPTION INFO  LINK TO ENSURE THAT YOU WILL MEET THE NECESSARY REQUIREMENTS TO ADOPT ONE OF OUR PETS.  THANK YOU. 

ADOPTION PROCESS and REQUIREMENTS :

animal.description:
*Currently on hold, pending *
Sarge is an American Bully male, slightly over one year in age.  He does have some issues that I will go into detail on......
He nips and controls the female in his home, his male adopter was a cop and doesn't put up with that so he mostly limits his "corrections" to "his" female. While working with him, he was submissive with me although he would sneak in a few nips. When I approach him to correct, he would submit but this guy does have a very strong personality and it is not only with his attempts to control his new owner of a few months, but also with his loyalty. He will "correct" his owners with barks and nips if ignored, if she does not play tug with him he will hit her with his tug toy. He will bark at her if she refuses to turn on the TV for him. I asked that I enter the backyard alone when I arrived where he was and he greeted a stranger with wags. He is very calm and well behaved in the house.

Now for his good traits...
He will sit for hours and watch Paw Patrol....no, really. He goes in his crate when asked. He rides like a human, sitting straight up in his seat and waits patiently while his female owner runs daily errands, enters business's and returns. He is well behaved to strangers. When I went over, he sat and waited for me to invite him into the house before entering when told, I also taught him to "bring it and drop" in a matter of minutes. He greets dogs on leash while hiking overly eager which does intimidate most dogs and their humans. **He should be an only dog until his control issues are controlled**. He still, did not like being corrected, clearly, but showed a 80 percent improvement after a few hours. He never bit me in an aggressive manner however Sarge is a large boy and will be placed as carefully.
Sarge is fully vetted, heart worm tested, all shots of course now neutered and micro chipped. He had a spider bite on his back which was infected and I had that treated, it is healed but does have scarring until his hair grows back and he comes with his doggy seat, and extra large crate. He is fully house broken. He is well above average intelligence, learns very quickly (within minutes) and is so loving, constantly wanting to be with his person and laying on my and their laps, with a personality so adorable that he can and will work his person into putty in his paws. I easily am able to take treats and toys away, he has no food aggression. I am able to pull on his teeth, toes, tail, put my face to his when eating.  
Sarge needs an adopter with time and training skills who can show him patience as well as guidance and be an only dog until his nipping is under control.  Will send in depth video to potentials.

animal.description:
Charlie is a 10 yr old 13 lb Pekingese/Pomeranian mix.   His previous owner heartlessly abandoned him at a park wearing just a flea collar. He was found early in the morning by a good samaritan who brought him home and called animal control to pick him up. 

It was clear that Charlie had not been properly cared for as he was flea infested, underweight and missing hair on his back and ears from flea-related dermatitis. 

We rescued Charlie from the shelter and brought him to our veterinarian for a full evaluation including a blood panel and urinalysis and he was found to be in good health with the exception of a heart murmur.  Charlie was evaluated by a cardiologist and has heart disease requiring daily medication.  He currently has no symptoms. Charlie had a recent dental cleaning and is up-to-date on all his vaccines.

He is an extremely sweet, gentle boy who loves everyone he meets.  Charlie LOVES other dogs, going on long walks and meeting new friends.  Charlie now has a gorgeous red, shiny coat and he doesn't shed!  

He is well mannered and completely house trained.  We would love for Charlie to have another doggy companion to hang out with.  Charlie is quite the ladies man!

If you are interested in Charlie, please complete the on-line application that can be found on our website: www.adoptmerescue.org or contact us for more information.  Local adoption only.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Achilles.  I am a 1 yr old cattle dog mix.  I was found as a stray with a littler of puppies in a field in rural Utah, so my history is a bit of a blur. I am very sweet, but very timid.  When I was first found I was absolutely terrified of people; but, after several months in my patient and loving foster home I am starting to trust them and come out of my shy shell (I really like my foster mom and will even ask for pets now).   Dogs are a whole 'nother story.  I love to play with other dogs! Other dogs give me the confidence I need to be around people so a home with at least one other dog is an absolute MUST for me.  I am crate-trained, house-broken and doing really well with my leash training.  My vaccinations are all up-to-date and I am neutered.  If you have experience with extremely shy dogs, have another confident dog in your home and are interested in meeting me, please contact kathie@herdinghaven.org

animal.description:
***Fence required***

Meet Joey. 

Joey is a sweet, affectionate, beautiful 10 month old great Dane who came into the rescue a couple of months ago after his owners surrendered him to us because he could not control his bowels. Joey was pooping incessantly and very sick, and they could not afford to take him to a vet.

When we got him into the rescue, he was skeletal and he had been dealing with incontinence for five months without treatment - according to the owners. 

We got him straight to our vet where fecal tests revealed that he had one of the worst cases of hookworms that our vet has ever seen. In addition to that, ultrasound and xrays showed the hookworms had seriously damaged his intestinal tract and lining - causing him to have a chronic case of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD). 

Joey went through several rounds of dewormer and antibiotics. Unfortunately, the hookworms did permanent damage to his stomach, so it is likely that Joey will always deal with IBD for the rest of his life. 

Joey requires a strict special diet, he can only have a specific sensitive-stomach food, and he takes a daily regimen of meds that he will also likely need to remain on for life. Even on all these meds though, he still has accidents at times. He has made huge improvements though since we’ve gotten him. His stools have firmed up a lot and he’s actually absorbing his food now, because he is no longer skin and bones. He also tries his best to make it outside to go potty.

Here’s the good news: Joey is one of the sweetest Danes you’ll ever meet. And he is SO VERY GOOD with other dogs. And kids. And adults. All of them. He doesn’t have a mean bone in him. He’s very playful and submissive. He’s still a goofy puppy too and he has no idea he’s any different. All he wants to do is play. He lives to play with others. 

Joey is going to need someone who is home a lot and has the PATIENCE of a saint. One that won’t fault him for something that is completely out of his control. He can’t always control his poop. That’s not likely to change. 

Joey will need someone whose house preferably isn’t covered in rugs or carpet, is easily cleanable. Frequent outdoor trips for potty break will be necessary. He also absolutely needs to have another dane or large breed dog to be his playmate and companion. He does deal with separation anxiety and is a magician at breaking out of a crate to be able to hang with the other dogs. If left out with them, he’s not destructive. He just wants to be near his family. But if you try to separate him from the others when gone, you may come home to a destroyed bathroom or crate (trust us). He DOES NOT like being separated. He is currently boarding with another Dane and does well.

We have not had Joey around any cats but we do not believe that he would ever be aggressive with them. He doesn’t have a mean bone in him, he may just try to play with them. 

He’s lived with young kids and been great.

Joey has a heart of gold. He just has specific special needs and will need a special person or family that can meet those needs. If you can, we promise you, he’s a gem. Could you be that person? 

Joey’s adoption fee is $400. To apply to adopt Joey please go to www.nwflgdr.com/adopt. 

ATTENTION: If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description: Meet Molly.  Molly is fostered in Rhode Island.  We were asked to take Molly in when her owner was very ill. Sadly her owner died just hours later.  Molly is approximately 7 years old.  While Molly has been fine with other dogs outside of her foster home she would prefer to be the only resident dog as that is all she’s ever known.   Molly knows “come”, “sit” and “paw”. She loves to go for walks and hang out in the yard. Molly has been very therapeutic for a volunteer who suffered the loss of a family member recently.  Maybe she understands what she’s going through as she lost her one and only family member.  She’d love to find a forever home where she doesn’t have to worry about being alone again - we are looking for a home without young children for Molly.   She must have a fenced in yard-no electric fences.  She is spayed, up to date on vaccinations and housebroken.. If interested in Molly please apply at Americanlabrescue.com.

animal.description:
Blackdog Club is a facility-based rescue. We are open to the public Wednesday-Sunday between 10-6. An appointment is not required. 

If an adopter wishes to bring a current pet for a meet/greet, please send vet records showing the pet is UTD on all vaccines prior to your visit to blackdogclub@outlook.com

The adoption fee includes spay or neuter, microchip, age-appropriate vaccines, rabies vaccine, fecal test, deworming, and heartworm test. Dogs are treated if heartworm positive. All dogs are UTD on heartworm/flea/tick prevention. All dogs are health screened and vaccinated by our vet, Family Pet Animal Hospital or Quality Care Animal Hospital.

We do not know if our dogs are house trained. They are crated overnight.
 
Dean is an oversized puppy. He came in with Sam 2. There were found as strays, turned over to Harnett Shelter and we pulled from there. We initially felt they were a bonded pair but have discovered they do great separated. Dean is learning basic manners and is working on leash training. He is the more submissive of the brothers. He enjoys playing with toys. Dean would make a great pet for an older child. No cats and he is dog selective. Estimated DOB: 10/09/2019. Current weight: approximately 75 lbs

animal.description: Muffin is a beautiful young pup with one floppy ear to give him some character. Muffin doesn't get caught up on his looks. Muffin's got things to do, he's a spicy pineapple. You see, Muffin's one of those dogs that wants to play ALL OF THE TIME! He's so very excited to meet other playmates, and if there are other dogs around, he's gonna to convince them that they want to play with him! Muffin is a survivor, having beat distemper, because of this he sometimes learns a bit differently. He has mastered sit and his foster mom is working on unique ways to teach him things. When you think about the definition of a 'normal dog', that may not be Muffin, but he is normal and perfect to us. Muffin has a lot of energy in all directions at once, and while he may not exactly have object-permanence down, he's an expert in playtime and looks for fun around every corner. Muffin's favorite toys can best be described as 'anything moving'. He will do zoomies with the resident dog in his foster home or on his own, he enjoys tug of war with stuffed animals and playing 'mouth' with his doggie friends. Hold onto those hollowed-out plush toys, because Muffin likes to throw them in the air and catch them. When Muffin finds a favorite plushie, he enjoys cuddling with it and occasionally grooming it. He also loves going on walks, is pretty good on leash and likes to stop a lot to look at stuff, especially if he can't figure out what it is. He's very alert to any weird sounds - if it's moving he should probably go try to play with it! When Muffin does stop moving, that means it's naptime, and he likes to lay on his human for that. He enjoys a good cuddle, but prefers sleeping separate and eats and sleeps overnight in his crate. He likes to kiss feet and hands very gently. He was particularly fond of his foster's mother and loved to melt into her whenever they would interact. As much as he loves people, Muffin often has a difficult time focusing, as he's constantly distracted by the next bit of fun he can see and sometimes seems to be ignoring potential adopters. But out on walks, he introduces himself to everyone he walks past and has an interest in runners (he'd likely make a nice jogging buddy). Overall, Muffin's entire mission in life is playing and finding ways to amuse himself. He also makes adorable 'gremlin noises'. Muffin is looking for an adopter that will understand that he has unique behavior quirks and medical challenges but everything is very manageable and APA is here to help! The ideal home for Muffin would have active people, a playful canine buddy to help burn off his energy, a yard to bound through and an unlimited supply of plushies and balls. If you're ready to be Muffin's forever playmate, come meet this great pup!
animal.name: Muffin

animal.description:
This is Harvey!  He's a young male adult, on the large side.  We think he might be an Akita mix.  He is handsome and playful!  Harvey can be fearful of new situations and can be unpredictable in his reactions, so he would do best  with an experienced owner.  We think that as he is exposed to more situations, he'll settle in nicely, but his new family will need to be watchful and patient.  New situations have caused him to nip, he is especially touchy with his neck area.  We are not recommending him for a home with young children.  Harvey can be very loving and is pretty good about entertaining himself in his kennel with some toys!  He hasn't quite grasped the concept of "fetch" but he does love to chase a ball!  He really seems to want to play with some of our other dogs, too!  Harvey has been neutered, and is ready for a fresh start in a new home!  Come check out Harvey and our other dogs available for adoption at 2650 Washington Blvd, Crescent City, CA 95531.

Please call us at (707) 464-7235 for additional information.  More photos of this dog may be available on the Dogs of Del Norte County Facebook page.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
GIORDANO is ADOPTABLE in NORTHERN CA!

Giordano is a 3.5-year old male Neapolitan Mastiff, and he is a BIG boy, weighing about 160#. Gio lived his entire previous life as an outside dog, and when the neighbors repeatedly complained about his barking, his previous owner dumped him at a high kill shelter. One of our rescue partners got Giordano out of the shelter, and he is now fully vetted. They've started working on training with him, and his future family will need to continue that, and work on socialization.

Giordano is potty trained, he knows "sit" and "down", and he takes treats nicely. He is not good on a leash, so needs work on that, and he startles from loud noises. Giordano has never been around other dogs, and he does not like cats, so he will need to be an only pet. It is very difficult to get Giordano into a car, so transporting him is NOT an option, and he must stay in Northern CA for that reason.

Giordano is an affectionate boy who enjoys being with his humans. He appeared not to know how to play when he first came home to foster, but with time he was tugging on a giant rope toy and running zoomies in the yard. He is very smart. He learns quickly. Positive reinforcement and chicken nuggets are his go to high value reward treat. Speaking of food, Giordano doesnt like to share, so during his meal times, he should be offered his meal and left alone to eat. Due to being undersocialized, he can become insecure in situations he has not encountered before. Loud noises will at times startle him. He can be cautious and slow to respond at times. He will require patience and experience as he adjusts to his new home. He just wants to be indoors and with his family.

We realize that Giordano's stunning looks will probably attract a lot of attention, and while lots of people may want him just because of that, he is NOT the dog for just anyone. We are looking for a very specific adopter for this boy, so please don't apply for him unless you fit all of the following parameters:

~ Must live within a 4-hour radius of Sacramento, CA
~ Must own your own home
~ Must have 6' fenced yard
~ Must have no children under 16-years old living in the home
~ Must have NO other pets
~ Must have Neo experience (or experience w/ Corso, Boerboel, Presa, Fila or Tibetan Mastiff is ok, too)
~ Must be willing to spend a lot of time with him and continue his training (Please have a plan for that)

Yep, we are basically looking for a unicorn, but we know the right family is out there somewhere!

~ If you fit ALL of the above criteria and you're interested in adopting Giordano, please complete a family profile on our website, and we'll get in touch with you. Thanks!

www.mastinorescue.org

1/28/21 2:54 PM

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Sweetie is a senior at 7-years old, and she found herself with us because her mom had to sell her home and move into an apartment, where Sweetie was not welcome. We couldn't let anything bad happen to her, so currently, Sweetie is temporarily camping out at Uncle Russ and Aunt Laura's house in Georgia, and transport is available to an approved home.

Sweetie is fully vetted and microchipped. She loves sitting in the back seat while going for car rides. She is leash and house trained, and overall, she's just a very good, easy going girl. Sweetie has been enjoying the company of a senior male Neo (Edsel, formerly Mastino Rescue's Luigi), and she loves playing with her 2 favorite toys and chilling on the sofa.

Our 110-pound, blue brindle beauty desires a quiet environment and an adoring mother to fuss over her. She does take to men and strangers, but a little added time is required, as this girl only knew one home and Mom her entire life, before now.

Shhhhh!! Uncle Russ told me not to tell anyone so please keep our little secret. Sweetie loves curling up in bed with him and Aunt Laura at night. :)

Sweetie is currently located in GA, but we can arrange transport to another State, if needed. If you can find it in your heart to give this sweet, senior Neo her forever after, please go to our website (www.mastinorescue.org) and complete a Family Profile, and then someone from our Adoption Team will contact you.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.PLEASE NOTE: YOSHI IS A COURTESY LISTED DOG AND NOT PART OF BFPA. PLEASE CONTACT THE OWNER WHO IS LISTED BELOW IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN KNOWING MORE ABOUT YOSHI.

Meet Yoshi, an 4 year old, 80 pound half Staffordshire Terrier and half Chow dog. He is neutered and up to date with all medical care. He is a wonderful companion and a protective dog who is looking for a new home.

Yoshi is friendly once he gets to know you. He usually barks at least once when someone new comes in the house. He does not always get along with dogs, so he needs a home where he is the only pup. Yoshi has not been around children or cats so I am not sure how he would react.

Yoshi is completely housebroken. He has gone up to 10 hours without having to go outside to do his business. At night he sleeps at the foot of my bed. He is well behaved in the house so no crate is needed. Yoshi's activity level is low, he loves to relax around the house and be my buddy. He walks fine on a leash if there are no other dogs. If we see another dog, he exhibits leash reactivity, therefore Yoshi needs a home with a fenced yard.

Yoshi's favorite thing is being near me, especially sitting on the back porch. Yoshi is looking for his forever home that will give him the love he deserves. Would you like to meet him and see if he could be your forever companion? For more information about this handsome dog, please contact Janice at jgodfrey64@gmail.com or 919-601-6485.

DISCLAIMER: We hope you'll consider adopting YOSHI. YOSHI is a courtesy listed dog. This means that he is not a part of or associated with Best Friend Pet Adoption (BFPA). The bio information listed for him was provided by his owner and not generated or verified by BFPA. Adoption arrangements will be a private arrangement between you and the owner. As with any dog adoption, BFPA encourages potential adopters to gain as much information as possible before adopting. This includes temperament testing and verification of vet records to ensure the dog is in good health, UTD on vaccinations and has been sterilized. For more information about this handsome dog, please contact Janice at jgodfrey64@gmail.com or 919-601-6485.

Also in need of a foster home ~ 
NMDOG JOURNEY is available for adoption. JOURNEY is a precious, AdoraBull girl & she is ready to learn what living as a treasured member of a family is all about! JOURNEY does need a home as the only dog. We are currently updating JOURNEYs Petfinder listing, please email Info@nmdog.org to learn more OR to save time, directly submit your application!! (see below for more info....) 

As an all volunteer, foster based, 501(c)3 non profit rescue, NMDOG is always in need of new, approved foster & adoptive homes in order to continue our Mission: to serve & protect New Mexico's Forgotten Dogs!! 

If you see a dog you are interested in that says "in need of a foster home", we are currently seeking a temporary foster home for that dog in order to provide them with the cozy & loving experience of a home environment while we work hard to find their forever family. This also frees up space & funds, which enables us to save another life. There is never a cost to foster for NMDOG & you will have the dedicated support of the NMDOG TEAM every step of the way. We take the time to really get to know the needs & personalities of our kids & we go the extra mile to ensure we make the best possible match...setting our dogs & their humans up for success! To learn more about the NMDOG foster program & to submit the foster application, please visit this link on our website - www.nmdog.org/foster

Our adoption fee is $250 which includes; a 7 week NMDOG obedience/bonding class with their new family (classes are located in Abq & are also offered to our foster guardians), a complimentary vet wellness check & our dogs come with all of the supplies they need to get started on a trial adoption in their new home. All adopted dogs also receive free or discounted goodies & services from many of our awesome community partners!! Grooming, food, training, boarding, pet sitting & more. To learn more about the NMDOG adoption process & to submit the adoption application, please visit this link on our website - www.nmdog.org/adopt 

NMDOG doesn't cut any corners when it comes to the care & placement of our dogs. When a dog enters the NMDOG program, they are guaranteed to receive the very best of care. All of our available dogs have received a full medical & behavioral clearance prior to placement. They are (at the very minimum) spayed or neutered, UTD on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped, dewormed, Heartworm tested & currently on HW/flea & tick preventative. Due to the nature of our work, many of the dogs we rescue need much more extensive care before they are cleared for adoption. At NMDOG, we stand by our dogs for life & we make a promise to always be there for them (& their people) should they ever need us. . 

Please contact us directly via the links provided above or email info@nmdog.org with your interest in becoming a treasured NMDOG Foster Guardian or FoReVeR Guardian Angel to one of our amazing dogs in need!
We look forward to hearing from you & answering any questions you may have. WooF!!

animal.description:
Meet Rollie (pronounced like Raleigh)! Rollie was a stray that was taken in at the end of August, and we think he is about 10 months old at the moment. Because he was a stray, his breed is a bit of a mystery, but his vet thinks he's an Anatolian Shepherd. He is already quite large for his age at about 60lbs. and will likely get to be 70lbs. or more. Rollie is a very smart dog who picks up on things quickly and is housebroken, but some more training on basic commands will do him well. He loves people and can get a bit anxious when left alone for too long, so he would love to be part of a family that could give him all the attention he craves.  Rollie generally is very calm but expressive, and he is usually content with just laying with you and soaking in the pets, watching tv, or just hanging out! That being said he is still very young (despite his size), so he needs a way to work off all that energy every day. His favorite way is a walk with lots of people and squirrels around, but he is also content with fetch in a backyard. He is a great and loving dog and would love to meet you!

If you are interested in providing a loving home to this pet please complete the L.A.P. application at, https://www.laprescue.org/adoption-app-.html
 or email us at LapRescue@gmail.com
Local area adoptions only. Home visits are required.
Even if you can't give this animal a home you can still help by making a donation to help with their care. Any amount you can spare will be sincerely appreciated. https://www.laprescue.org/donate.html
Thank You!

They are both about 2 years old and almost identical in appearance and weight - one is 51 pounds, the other 52, one is lighter brindle and white, the other darker brindle and white. Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers. 

This pet and many others are available for adoption from the Cobb County Animal Shelter 1060 Al Bishop Dr. Marietta, GA 30008, call (770) 499-4136 for more information. Shelter hours are: Tues. - Sun. 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. by appointment only until further notice, CLOSED Mondays & Holidays.

animal.description:
Mira is sweet, though only with those she knows and loves, which takes some time! She is part of the initiation process at the Milo Sanctuary --- not a dog for the faint of heart! A fun and lovable little toughie. Since coming to the sanctuary she has won the hearts of every person she has met, which is no surprise considering she is absolutely adorable! Mira would be happy going for hikes, she's great off leash in the country with a pack, she;s into finding adventures or just cuddling on the couch all day, though she does love adventure and needs exercise. 
Mira loves people, but needs quite some time to warm up to strangers and does have the propensity to snap, when reached for, handled at her neck/collar, and if spooked or forced into interactions she isn't ready for. Because of this a home with children, or people who think they know better and will push her, would NOT be a good fit for her. With time and the proper introductions and get acquainted period, she is more than willing to roll over for belly rubs, play and give/get lots of kisses, and her nicer play bites. Mira has lived with both cats and dogs and got along with all of them very well. She is a truly "special" little dog and will make the right adopters, those who love a sense of adventure and are quick on their feet, with their hands and like a good laugh, very happy. She loves riding in vehicles too.

If you feel you and Mira could be a good match, and you don't have children or a social epicenter for a home environment - fun loving adults and other dogs are fine! Please send an inquiry and an adoption questionnaire to: lat@milofoundation.org

animal.description: Cowboy is a beautiful smart boy who will make a wonderful forever friend for the right person. He already knows sit and to go to his crate when asked but would love to learn new tricks. He's house trained and looking for a loving indoor home. This wonderful boy has had a hard time finding his perfect match because everyone is attracted to his good looks, his love of fetch, the fact that he's dog friendly and very loving to his people BUT they forget that they have to love all of him and he does have fear aggression- this leads to lots of applicants who aren't a good match. His fear aggression means that he needs to be muzzled when around new people and is only recommended for homes without children. He will do best in a structured loving home. He's energetic and loves walks, adventures, and play time (did we mention how much he loves fetch!). Cowboy is a Texas boy with a big heart and just needs to find someone who will love him despite his initial shy nature which can lead him to be reactive. We promise that once he knows you he will LOVE you! No cats for this Cowboy.

Good with older children

Hello, Bologna here. Rumor has it that you are looking for a beagle to complete your family. Well, I think I can help you out in that area. Coincidentally, I'm a beagle looking to find a family of my own.

I am a pretty quiet boy. Nothing beats a good nap. As a matter of fact, I enjoy sleeping in, especially when I can lounge in bed snuggling with my humans and getting belly rubs. What a wonderful way to start the day! I've also discovered resting in the sunshine. Now that's a relaxing activity that can be enjoyed both with some company or solo.

I am coming along very well on my house training; I am 90 percent perfect! Another plus is that I walk quite nicely on my leash. I admit that some loud noises do make me jump. At first it can be very scary, but once I figure out where the noise came from, I am fine. For example, my foster mom takes me for a walk near some train tracks. The first time I heard the train's horn, I nearly jumped out of my fur! But since then, I don't even acknowledge that annoying horn... no need, since I now know what it is.

Did I mention that I just love to be with my humans? I will get in their laps whenever I can and encourage them to hold me like a baby. If my humans seem to want to get up, I will drape my body across their laps and hold them in position. There, now isn't that better?

I also value my relationships with other canines and often spend time playing with my foster sister. It would be ideal if my new home had at least one other canine companion to keep me company. That would certainly be better than having to be alone. No one likes to be by themselves.

I do hope that my new home is calm and peaceful. I'd rather not deal with chaos and excess noise. So, if you have a loving home that just needs a sweet and gentle beagle, I may just be the one you are seeking. Can't wait to meet you!



------

animal.description:
Do you need a little Cinnamon in your life? 

We know where you can find one! Meet our Cinnamon; the most affectionate and lovable Dachshund mix you will ever meet. And when we say affectionate, that's an understatement. He loves to curl up next to his human or take up all the space on your lap. He is good with other pups and loves to play. Do you like walks? Cinnamon does! He would be happier than anything to be your companion exploring the grass and flowers in the neighborhood. He's a man with small needs. A fenced backyard will keep him happy and safe to roam around in.

Cinnamon's beautiful eyes do not produce enough tears. This will be a health condition that is life-long for him. But do not fear! It's simple. All he needs is his human to apply a DAILY prescription eye ointment (Optimune) and take him in for regular check-ups to monitor his eyes. If he's not getting his daily ointment, it will be very painful for him and his beautiful eyes will be prone to infections. Can you help him this little man?

He is waiting for you to open your heart to him and bring him home. 

Adoption Fee: $350
San Francisco Bay Area adoption only.

If you would like to meet Cinnamon, please apply at http://www.lovewoof.org/our-animals:

Adoption Process:
Once an adoption counselor receives and approves your application, they will contact you (only if you match the animal's needs) to set up an appointment to meet the dog you applied for and/or any of the other dogs in the rescue. If the dog you applied for is not a good match for your particular situation, there might be others that are better matches.

Adoption Fees:
Adoption fees allow WOOF Animal Rescue to continue to provide care and medical treatment (including spay/neuter services) for dogs while we look for their forever homes. The fees also helps cover the ongoing costs of caring for less adoptable dogs that require longer stays in the rescue, or more advanced medical treatment before finding their forever homes.

WOOF Animal Rescue, in Fremont CA, does not have a shelter, all of our dogs are raised in foster homes. Each dog comes spayed or neutered, up to date on vaccinations and rabies shots appropriate for their age, dewormed and microchipped.

animal.description: All of our dogs are Spayed/Neutered, Micro-chipped, and up to date on shots before being released to adopters.NAME:MaxxSTATS:Male, Cane Corso and Great Dane Mix, 1.5 years estimate, 115 lbs.TEMPERAMENT:Shy at first and warms up.Needs seasoned owner to work with issues (see below).ActiveInitially was told he was fearful of men, which seems to be he just needs slow introductions to new people where he can approach them at his own pace. Warms up quickly to men and women as long as it is done slowly and at his pace. Initially weary of strangers. SKILLSPotty trained.Crate trained.Older children in a savvy home only (12+)Has not been exposed to cats.Has not been exposed to other dogs and looking to place as an only dog at this time.MORE ABOUT ME:Likes belly rubs.Needs patient proactive owner willing to work on behavior (see details below).Signing up for basic training will be a requirement to adopt. EXPERIENCED/large breed savvy owners required.ONE LAST THING:Maxx is a supersized puppy with lots of attention and love to give to the right family. He is goofy and loves to play, especially with an appropriately sized toy like his JUMBO Jolly-Ball. He loves treats and while he is a little on the shy side at first with new people, he warms up quickly as long as it is done at his pace. After the initial warm up phase, his true personality comes out. There is a playful side to him as well as a lazy lay at your feet side, although sometimes he may mistakenly lay on your feet in his attempt to cuddle :).Maxx initially had negative reactions when it came to strangers and pretty much everything new to him (including swaying palm trees). With reassurance, positive reinforcement in the form of treats, and looking to his handler for a confidence boost, his triggers have lost power. He will need continued socialization, desensitization, and training. With the right forever home, Maxx will continue to improve. He picks up on things very quickly and is very treat and toy motivated. He does need someone who will be patient with him, but also serve as someone who he can turn to for confidence and stability when he is unsure or frightened of something new for reassurance. If you you are interested in meeting one of the dogs, please fill out an application from our website at www.K9PawPrintRescue.org. We are always in need of fosters and volunteers

animal.description:
Please click "MORE ABOUT US" at the right and read about our adoption process before contacting B.O.N.E.S.



4.5 year old male
**Needs a Physically Fenced Yard**
Good with dogs
Unsure about cats
Good with older children

Hi there, I'm Bartleby, but my friends just call me Bart. I'm in the market for a home of my own. If you're looking for a new furry family member, we just may be meant for each other.

I am a very good boy, and I'm happy to express my gratitude to my humans for rescuing me. My face often says "I love you," and my snuggles just reinforce it. As a matter of fact, I love people so much that I am much happier when my human is home for at least a good part of the day. Of course, I also love other dogs and would not mind having some canine companionship as well.

I already know some things that will surely make my new humans happy. I am house trained as well as crate trained, although I am well behaved enough that I don't need to use the crate at all. I even know the commands "sit" and "come" and am eager to learn as much as you want to teach me.

Some of my favorite activities are chilling with my foster siblings, playing with my toys, and running around the yard trying to identify all the wonderful scents... squirrel, chipmunk, hmmmm.... stinky.... oh, skunk! I'll stay away from that one! I don't even mind inclement weather. I'll happily run around in the rain. It's fun!

My foster parents say I'm a very sweet pup. I think they are pretty special, too. I really do like being a loved family member. I am pretty brave because thunder and fireworks do not faze me. They're just loud noises. However, that vacuum has got to go. No, it's not just a loud noise. That machine makes things disappear! I saw a fur ball, and then it was gone! I'm staying as far away from that thing as possible. I don't want to get sucked into it.

While I like playing and being active, cuddling up with my family is awesome. At night, I hop into bed with everyone and curl up for a cozy night's sleep. There really is nothing better than being loved. Now that you know all about me, I sure hope you will consider welcoming me into your family. I would be forever grateful.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Betty and Barney

Betty is a CoJack (Corgi-Jack Russell) girl of about 3-4 years of age found wandering on the streets. Betty had been there for a while and was living on garbage. This sweet girl was picked up on a 106-degree day dehydrated and weak by a Bakersfield rescue group that rescues street dogs. Barney is a Corgi-Jack Russell boy of about 6 years of age who was also picked up as a stray and cared for by his finder until she found us to take him in.

Betty and Barney have been in foster care. They have developed a deep bond being with one another and do everything together. They are like a little married couple, it is sooo cute!

Both dogs love attention, are super sweet and cuddly, love their daily walks on a lead and hanging out with their foster mom. They will benefit by being with a retired individual or couple who will have more time to spend with them. Both dogs love their walks, exploring and seeing new things. They will also lose weight faster and rebuild their muscles the more they get out and exercise, so an active person or couple is a must for these two sweeties

Betty and Barney have been treated for Parasites and are up to date on their vaccines. Both dogs are being fed a diet of Human Grade Dog food and Raw dog food. Both dogs receive supplements for health, joint care, and weight loss. Betty had come in bloated and heavy from living on garbage as a stray. Barney was overfed by the person who rescued him. Heather, their foster mom has been working to trim them down and rebuild their muscle mass. Both are looking wonderful, have trimmed down and are happy dogs.

Rompin Paws Rescue will educate the adopters on species-specific feeding and Canine nutrition for longevity, ultimate health, and vitality.

To fill out an application to adopt Please use this link, You will need a computer to complete as cell phones will drop the application. Betty and Bareny have a bonded pair adoption fee of $1050.00. this covers their neuters, all vaccines and rabies and their care. All monies are recycled to save more dogs

http://rompinpawsrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/

The site will ask you to create a password and will send you an email. For ease of use, just use the password they create for you and save that password. This will ensure you have access and can fill out the application.

Stallone - Golden/Chow Mix - Male - 7 Years - www.twyla.org

If you'd like to know more about this dog please visit our website at www.Twyla.org

Meet Stallone: this gorgeous Golden Retriever/Shepherd/Chow Mix (we think) came to us as an owner surrender just before he was headed to the pound. He had spend the majority of his previous life outside in a not-so-large yard and while he is quite people friendly and outgoing, he doesn't know a lot about house rules and polite leash walking and people greeting. He is very much a "Diamond in the rough with a little dirt on it", he is food motivated and learns quickly, but is also a little stubborn and single-minded: he LOVES squirrels - likely one of his few entertainments in his small yard. He gets along well with other dogs after proper introduction - due to his lack of knowledge of rules and manners he tends to be inappropriate and a little "humpy". He is reasonably polite when meeting other dogs but would much prefer to be the only dog in his home.

Stallone is looking for a moderately dog-experienced home without another dog in it, older kids may be fine. He has moderate exercise requirements and a good daily walk should suffice for him.

***Please note: All dogs are fostered in private homes of volunteers, so to meet a dog please fill out an Adoption Application on our website (http://www.twyla.org/adopt/our-adoption-process) so we may setup a private meetup with the dog or coordinate for an Introduction at the next general Adoption Meet  and Greet (as listed on our website: (http://www.twyla.org/upcoming-events), as not all dogs attend all Meet and Greets***

animal.description:
Our Lizzie Baby is ready for adoption and looking for her forever home!!

She is about 2 years old, and currently in Washington state with her AMAZING foster family and Dogo foster brother. Her foster family has worked so hard with her - she has been going through training and socializing and is becoming a very good girl!

Lizzie Baby loves playing, running, cuddling, and chicken nuggets (who doesn’t?!) She is food motivated and willing to learn.

Her ideal home would be one with a large yard and an extra tall fence (she can climb a chain link fence!) Lizzie Baby needs a family who has Dogo/large breed experience who will understand all of her quirks and needs. Someone who is extra patient with her as she is still learning.

Lizzie Baby can be around male dogs if the family is very experienced. She is learning to be around cats, and is ok with them most of the time, but her ideal home would be one where she is the only pet and can receive all the attention. She is very loving, but we do not feel she would do best in a home with children at this time.

Dogos are a wonderful breed but we urge anyone interested to dig in and do a lot of research before deciding if they are a good fit for your home. They require a lot of attention and training with them never ends!  Boundaries must be enforced and they often need reminders as they push past boundaires you set! Dogos are loving, kind and gentle but don't mistake that for weakness because they are equally powerful and intense as well! Everyone in the home must be on board with having a dogo and play a major role in their daily routines and training. Yes it is work, but the rewards are ten-fold! Lazy homes don't work for dogos as they need stimulation, exercise, and lots of attention too during their younger years.  Our goal in rescue is to be as transparent as we can about each and every dog plus make sure new families really understand the needs of a dogo!

animal.description:
Brisby is a 4 year old Red and White Border/Aussie Mix. He weighs around 45 pounds. Brisby is an outgoing pup who loves to meet new people. He can be very bouncy with new humans.  Brisby is super sweet and thinks he is a lap dog. He's good with men and women, he's quite velcro, but he doesn't seem anxious when people leave him.

Brisby is very calm in his New York foster apartment, but he seems a bit bored. He could really benefit from having access to a yard, and daily stimulation and exercise. He hates loud booms (got seriously frightened on New Year's Eve from the amateur fireworks going off -- it took him hours to calm down). He is a sweet dog, but not a lapdog -- he likes to watch and monitor his people from across the room, preferably where he can see all of them at once.

?Brisby will take your arm off to run after a squirrel. His strong prey drive means that you have to have a plan when walking him near trees. High-value treats and a lot of walking practice have helped, but his next owner should be prepared to work on his chase habit to make walks safe and enjoyable for everyone. 

Brisby's prey drive is also strong enough to suggest that he cannot share a home with cats (he almost went through a cemetery fence trying to catch a neighborhood stray). Brisby is GREAT with people -- quite calm, especially with coaching. But Brisby lunges at dogs -- even after a lot of training walks -- so that can make walks a little stressful.?

Brisby does great sleeping in a kennel overnight, but he's not crazy about being left in the kennel while his people are out of the house (prepare to return home and find that everything you placed on top of the kennel is now next to the kennel -- that kind of thing). It seems safe to say now that Brisby is housebroken, and he's easy to read when he wants to go out, but he is leaky -- he wets a bit in his sleep if he hasn't gone out recently (just little spots you'll notice on his belly).

Brisby is fostered in New York, NY.

To apply to adopt visit www.ns4ar.org

They require a lot of attention and training with them never ends!  Boundaries must be enforced and they often need reminders as they push past boundaires you set! Dogos are loving, kind and gentle but don't mistake that for weakness because they are equally powerful and intense as well! Everyone in the home must be on board with having a dogo and play a major role in their daily routines and training. Yes it is work, but the rewards are ten-fold! Lazy homes don't work for dogos as they need stimulation, exercise, and lots of attention too during their younger years.  Our goal in rescue is to be as transparent as we can about each and every dog plus make sure new families really understand the needs of a dogo!

DOB: ~01/04/2016
Weight: 100 lbs
Energy Level: Medium-High
Personality Type: Snuggly, Loyal, Independent, People-Oriented 
History: Transferred from another shelter/owner surrender
Fence Requirements: Physical fence required.
Ideal Home: Active family! Breed experience preferred.
Special Info: Please research the breed before applying! Nokosi is very much a Malamute!

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.
