animal.description: Hey there friends!! Meet Buddy!!! Buddy is a 5 year old, pitty/beagle mix, and he is just the most handsome boy!!! Buddy was surrendered to us due to his pervious family moving and being unable to take him with them due to his breed! Buddy had been with them his whole life as their indoor, family dog!! The previous owners described him as well behaved, active, and playful!! They also said he did well with their children!! Buddy is a large and confident boy. Sometimes he even thinks he is the boss, lol! But he is smart, he takes commands, he loves to play, and is BEYOND loyal to his people. He knows how to sit, shake, fetch (even though he doesn't always bring it right back lol), and he is house broken!! Unfortunately, Buddy was not very socialized with other animals. Therefore, he will need to be the only animal in the home. He can also be timid and cautious when meeting new people! So his new owners would have to be understanding of his need to be introduced slowly! However, once he warms up he is a really sweet and playful doggy!! He does tend to bark at people and other animals that he is not familiar with, but it is just because he is uncomfortable, once he actually meets the person he calms right down!!! He has been with us for a little while and we are really hoping to find him his forever home soon!! He is neutered, vaccinated, and dewormed! His adoption fee is $80!! Who out there is willing to give this very sweet boy a chance??!? He MORE than deserves it!!

animal.description:
Hello! My name is Olympia. My foster mom calls me Limpy. I’m a female 8 month old medium-sized (33 pounds) Staffie/Cattle dog/Chihuahua mix originally from New Orleans. I’m visually impaired but my keen hearing and sense of smell help me get around with ease. My whole backside wags all the time because I am so happy! 

I am crate trained and even know a few commands such as sit, paw and will nudge the bell to be let outside. I think I finally got this potty training thing down but please be patient with me as I’m still a puppy. 

My foster brother is over 90 pounds but that doesn’t stop me from trying to battle with him on a daily basis, however, I can also entertain myself. Because I have a lot of energy, my ideal home would be with another playful dog and a fenced yard for me to run. Walks are more fun with my foster brother who helps to guide me on the path. I do well around other dogs but haven’t had a chance to learn about cats yet. Young children might be scared by my jumpiness since I hold up my paws to learn about things around me but I'm working on the command "down". I am spayed, microchipped, and UTD on my shots.  Do you have room in your heart and in your home for me?

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please review our adoption policies and apply online at [www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt](http://www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt).

Visit [www.speakfortheunspoken.com](http://www.speakfortheunspoken.com/) will give you more information about our rescue.

***PLEASE READ*** WE DO NOT RESPOND TO PETFINDER OR EMAIL INQUIRIES. Please fill out an application on our website if you are interested in adopting this dog. We will only set up a meeting with the dog once you have an approved adoption application. We actively manage our dogs on Petfinder, the dogs listed are available for adoption. animal.description:
CROSS POST: **Please read Mia's entire profile, which includes a link to the adoption application. She is at GREAT DOG NEW ENGLAND, not Rock n' Rescue. Thank you!**

Meet Mia - a 2 year old, 55 pound, Plott Hound mix gal.

Mia is looking for a very special family! Mia is an active girl who loves to run and play fetch. She will need a fenced in yard. If you do not have a fenced in yard, she needs a quiet neighborhood and needs to work on walking on a leash. Mia is a rough player with other dogs so we suggest she is the only dog in the home. She is not aggressive with other dogs so we think she will do fine with play dates - she just prefers to get all your attention. She also should not live with cats. She rides well in the car and can use more leash training as she is very barky when approaching other dogs on a walk. She is great with little kids - very patient and affectionate with little ones and happy to run and play with bigger kids. She’s crate trained, knows ‘sit’ & ‘wait’ and that ‘go nunnites’ means to go to her dog bed in the bedroom to go to bed for the night. She will bark for a moment at guests when they come over but she stops once they can meet and people really love her.

Mia is epileptic, and is on a few daily medications. She has an emergency med for the 24 hours after she has a seizure and uses CBD oil daily. With her meds and the new CBD oil, she’s been seizure free for over a month now. She will need to see a vet every 6 months to take blood to make sure her blood levels are okay on her current meds.

Mia is going to require a patient owner who can deal with managing her energy and her epilepsy - but anyone who takes this on is going to feel the rewards of her love and affection for years to come!
All dogs are up to date on vaccinations and spayed/neutered at the time of adoption. All dogs require professional training to become the best family member they can be.

To adopt or learn more about Mia, you must fill out an adoption application. To find the application, copy and paste this URL into your browser: WWW.GDRNE.COM/ADOPTION-APPLICATION [Adoption Fee: $495] ** PLEASE READ: If a dog is listed, then s/he is currently available for adoption. Their information is correct to the best of our abilities and the information we have been given as of the day of posting. Please note, GDRNE does not guarantee the breed of any dog or puppy unless stated that we have run DNA. All breeds listed are educated estimates. Our dogs are rescued from various situations. It is most likely that both their parents were strays and even if not, mixes of some sort and that their grandparents were mixes as well. The dog may have some genetic material of an American Staffordshire Terrier (pit bull). The dogs are usually mixes of many breeds, making them a breed all their own - a True and adorable American MUTT. If you are interested in this dog, you must submit an application. Great Dog is not a shelter so there is no building you can visit. Our dogs live in private foster homes until adopted. To learn more about our *shelterless* rescue, adoption fees, and procedures, review the list of Frequently Asked Questions on our website at WWW.GDRNE.COM.

animal.description:
I am a sweet young lady looking for a loving home. I came to the shelter and having had a serious old injury or birth defect to my back, leaving me looking a bit different. I will need, at the very least, a lifetime of close monitoring, joint supplementation and supportive medications as needed. The vet I saw here feels I would do best having a neurology consult, and there is not someone locally that specializes in canine neurology. There may be many therapies that benefit me in the long run, and I need an adopter willing and able to take on the potential long term needs I have. All I want to do is cuddle and play. If you are looking for a worthy and devoted life partner, who needs a leg up, as they say, please ask to meet me! 
My foster says I am a true joy: I'm affectionate, playful, smart, and energetic. I love to snuggle up with anyone who will sit on a couch -- or the floor-- with me. I warm up quickly to strangers, and am super-excited to see other creatures outside. (That is, I bark at every deer, squirrel, chipmunk, bird, etc.:) I learn things very quickly such as wiping my feet when I come in the door!

NOTE: Please read our entire write-up before contacting us. If you don't know the age, breed, weight, what vet care we provide our dogs, the adoption fee, or how to apply, you have not read the write-up. 

Coach

Breed: Shih Tzu mix
Gender: Male, neutered
DOB:   9-27-2004
Weight:  ~8 pounds  
Microchipped  
Adoption Fee:  $75

This old boy had a loving family that grew forgetful and were no longer able to remember to feed him and groom him properly. They surrendered him to a vet we know and so he came to us. Coach is a lovely old boy and is very affectionate! He just needs a home where he can live out his final years in peace, with comfort and companionship. No heroics are required, just good food, preventative meds (heartworm and flea) and regular grooming! He's a nice dog that was loved and deserves a loving home once again!

Coach has had a recent dental and tested negative for heartworms. He's deaf and blind, but is surprisingly good at navigating his world! He has learned his foster home, goes to the door to be let out for potty breaks and LOVES his time in the fenced in yard! He's an amazing little guy who is also a bit of a velcro dog!

Good w/ Other Dogs- Yes
Good w/ Cats- Probably
Energy Level- Low
Children- Adult home preferred
Grooming Needs- High
Walks on Leash- Yes
Special Needs- Elderly
Knows basic commands- Somewhat
Experienced Home- Required
Good First Time Dog- Require experience
Rides well in car-  Yes, crated
Crate Trained-  Yes
Low Allergen- Yes
Good apartment dog- first floor possibly    

Adoptive homes within the  Raleigh, NC area preferred.

2yrs old. She is a small/medium size weighing about 30-35lbs. Timid girl (has shown great improvement now since taking her in months ago). She was rescued from a shelter along with her newborn pups. 


UPDATE FROM FOSTER - 10/15 :
"Lolly is a very sweet girl. When she was rescued, she was extremely scared of everything when she arrived (video on facebook). 

Since then, Lolly has blossomed into a very sweet loving dog. She still does get scared in new surroundings and takes a little while to warm up to new people, but once she knows she can trust you, she will be your best friend. Lolly does get very excited for attention and loves belly rubs. She has not given kisses but she is not afraid to stick her nose in your face to let you know when she wants your attention. 

She is crate trained and is partially house trained. She does have accidents when she gets scared. She rides very well in cars. She does well on a harness and leash. She is good for baths and will need to be brushed about once a week. She does shed some.  She is protective of her food around cats, especially. Otherwise, she does well with dogs and cats after slow introductions. 

Lolly is a bit hand shy about anything going over her head. She just gets a little nervous. We have been working with her to help this. It would just need to be reinforced by her new owner. 

She would do well in a quieter home with, hopefully, someone who is around often. She will just need to be worked with slowly to help experience the world and grow more confident in her surroundings. Given love, patience, and time - Lolly can become a truly amazing dog."




Fee is $275

Kitty is a seven-year-old female Boxer Shepherd mix. Healthy, vaccinated, microchipped, and spayed.

We were lucky to rescue her from the Downey shelter, and now she is so happy to be in a foster home. Here, Kitty gets to go to the Laguna Beach dog park and even goes to work at her foster's store. animal.description:
Ben is a highly intelligent and loving dog in need of an owner with an active lifestyle.  Ben will thrive given a thorough and committed training and exercise plan.  He adores playing ball, and if the ball or toy squeaks, all the better.  He will be at your side even when just doing chores but would love to be active in agility or tracking.  Ben needs to be the only dog in the home, no cats or any other small animals!  

The Belgian Malinois breed dates back to the 1800s.  This intelligent and highly trainability breed was originally bred as a sheep-herding dog, 

The dogs in our program come with an additional four weeks of integration training after adoption. Integration training is one-on-one training with you, your new pet, and a trainer at Clearwater Dog Training, 1446 Estes St. Lakewood, CO  80215   For this reason we do not adopt dogs out of state.

At NSC, we believe the key to a successful placement is proper training. This way the dog knows what is expected of him, and you know how to communicate effectively with your dog. 

If you would like more information or even better would like to meet this dog, please contact Gina at 720-514-2543 or at gina@nscrescue.org. Meet and greet appointments are available M-T & Saturdays.

Please visit www.nscrescue.org to complete an adoption application to help us know a little about you.

We try to the best of our ability to represent the breed, age, and health as accurately as possible; however, as many of these animals come to us with no previous history, in some cases we are going off of educated guesses. Please be aware that while many dogs may appear purebred, there is no guarantee without a DNA check.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Mike (mike.finucane66@gmail.com) for more information about this pet.
Online Adoption Application 
Animal Profile:

- Pet Name: Bo
- Primary Breed: WCAC has Bo listed as Akita/ Mixed Breed. The current fosters also fostered in March 2020 Bo's sibling brother and litter mate Didley before rehoming Didley. The fosters had a DNA analysis done on Didley which reflected 36.5% Chow Chow, 16% Redbone Coonhound, 10% Australian Shepherd, 8.5% Border Collie, 7% German Shepard , 6% Collie, 16% Supermutt.
- Age: DOB 6/5/2018 - 2 years 4 Months
- Gender: Male Neutered
- Color: Solid Dark Blonde with light Tan underbelly.
- Estimated weight: Approx 50 lbs.
- Size: Medium
- Microchip Info: 985112009463145 (Home Again)

Current Situation:

Currently, Bo is with WCAC volunteers Mike & Cyndi Finucane who are fostering him in their home. He has been with us for one (1) week) and has done well following another short shelter stay after a likely high stress home environment, particularly when the adopter husband was present. Care should be given introducing new men to BO. Bo will likely not engage them and the strange man should not push himself on Bo for the introduction. Trust takes time with Bo particularly with men. It is not likely Bo will bond with men quickly.
It has taken Bo several days in our home for him to begin to relax and settle in. He is respectful in the home; no marking or accidents so we are comfortable saying he is housebroken. He does not chew and he enjoys his 'quiet time' usually in a crate with door open. We have the crate placed near where we spend most of our day when inside. He does not like the crate door closed so we would not consider him crate trained. Bo is a slow eater in the AM but eats a healthy early evening meal of dry kibble with goodies added in: (chicken (thighs, livers or gizzards), green beans, squash, cottage cheese, pumpkin (AM) etc.
Bo is very respectful of our two female smaller senior dogs 14 & 11 years of age and has bonded with and plays well with our 2 year old male Coonhound both in the house and in our fenced yard. I would describe their play style as low level rough & rowdy wrestle with occasional chase in the yard. He loves his long walks and the freedom of his fenced back yard with our other dogs. Bo lays quietly with us and our other three dogs following his last walk after evening meal as the household unwinds before last potty break and bedtime. He sleeps all night in his dog bed.

Behavioral Observations: 9/30/20 to Present

- Good with Children: Unknown but would suggest older children who can respect the dog and his personality.
- Housebroken: Yes
- Crate Trained: Partially. Bo will go into his crate for quiet time and naps but does not like the crate door closed.
- Friendly: Yes to women he knows and has established a relationship and trust with. He prefers women versus men. Once again with time and trust established with a man he will tolerate a man but not necessarily readily engage with affection and play. He will allow men to walk him. It is not likely that Bo will bond with men quickly.
- Commands: Knows Sit and wait for leashing up. Will sit for treats. Will wait at thresholds once the wait command is given and then 'OK' or 'Yes' for release.
- Submissive: Yes towards women he knows and has a relationship with.
- Chews: No
- Jumps: Occasionally when excited to see women he knows.
- Chases: Occasionally with his selective dog companion in play. Has not displayed any predator drive (chasing squirrels, rabbits etc.)
- Good with Dogs: Tolerant of all but Selective with his companions.
- Special Needs: None
- Playful: Occasionally on his terms. has not shown interest in play toys.
- Leash Trained; Yes. Does well on a slip lead harness and or Martingale flat collar.
- Claws: No
- Destructive: No
- Good with Cats: Unknown
- Noisy: No. Is a very quiet dog
- Aggressive: No. Has shown no resource guarding of food, water, treats, toys or places (dog beds, crates etc.) Has shown No aggression toward other dogs or people.
- Digs: No
- Fears: Can be fearful of new people, places and experiences. This is overcome in time with a 'GO SLOW' approach in all things new.

animal.description:
Anoemy was saved from a high kill shelter in Texas . 

Anoemy was clearly afraid and showed severe her teeth to the vet staff in Texas . Every day she became more aggressive when vet staff wanted to take her out of the kennel . 

When we have dogs that are a high risk for the public we have no other choice then to put them down but my instinct said there is more going on . 
I called the owner of our boarding place in Texas to do some test after one of the girls was bitten in her leg . The tests were negative but Anoemy has now a bite record and the staff became afraid of her . 

Before everybody becomes a keyboard warrior . Dogs who are coming from the kill shelters are on a transport of 4 hours long . They come in a hospital environment with strange noises and smells and easily become aggressive. On top of that most of our dogs are highly abused . The fear is real and a bite is not far off . This is one of the reasons why we have often months dogs in our kennels to let them decompress and will NEVER adopt straight from transport . 

Unfortunately our boarding place was full and time was ticking . Anoemy could not stay at our vet and became a high risk for the staff . Luckily a befriended rescue give me the name of another boarding place who was specialized in aggressive dogs . 

It was love on first sight. Anoemy went in Austin te but after that she was swimming in the owner his swimming pool. Anoemy was relaxed and sweet . The whole placed adored her and had tears when she was leaving For NY . 

She went In boarding at our vet in Huntington and a little bit later she started to limp . X -rays were taken and Anoemy needed a TPLO surgery and a FHO after they saw that she had hip dysplasia and a torn cruciate . 

Anoemy became a gorgeous full fur dog again after intens rehab for months and is doing great. 

As a rescue we have to tell you that she has a bite record at the vet in Texas . At our vet in NY she gave no problems and was a total sweetheart . 

She is 4.5 years old and needs to be pet only . 

She is active but extreme hiking is not allowed . 

Anoemy is an alpha dog and would be better placed by experienced shepherd owners . Adult only homes . 

She is located in Middle Island NY 

We would love to see this sweet lady who overcome her abuse in a loving home before the holidays. 

To become her new family please fill in the adoption link to find on our website ww.a-teameliterescuedogs.com or email us and we send you one

Good with dogs:  yes
Good with cats:  unsure
Good with kids:  no
Energy level:  medium
Good with men/strangers:  yes
Hypoallergenic:  no, sheds slightly

Special home requirements or medical:  adult only, calm environment home

Additional info:

Bruno is a pretty mellow guy, walks well on leash and is crate trained. He can be a bit temperamental and likes to push boundaries to see how far he can get so it’s important that Bruno be in an environment that can offer him structure and with someone that is confident. He doesn’t like to be bothered when he is sleeping or resting in his area but this does subside once he learns to trust you. He does have some resource guarding issues and a protective nature, so for this reason Bruno should be in an adult only home that has a calm environment that will provide him with the structure that he needs. He is a pretty independent and confident dog so we are looking for a human to match.

Bruno does enjoy playing with other dogs around his size but has some leash aggression so he is currently using a “gentle leader” head collar and is showing improvement already in just a week. This cute little guy just needs to be with someone that has the time and patience to continue to work with him on training and he really is a great dog.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

animal.description:
NOTE: This is a courtesy posting for another rescuer. Please do not contact ARRF, as we do not know this pet personally. To meet Boris, see the contact information below.

FCIA rescued Boris, a Rottweiler mix, from the shelter after his previous owner surrendered him due to his medical needs. He is 5 years old and weighs 82 pounds. He was suffering from chronic fungal and bacterial skin infections that had left him nearly bald, underweight, and with severe ear infections. Despite this, he remained very sweet and loving. After almost a year in our care that included intense and frequent medical tests and treatment, he is finally medically stabilized. He is happy, healthy and his coat is full and lush. Boris will require lifelong medication and routine vet checks. He is now on thyroid meds 2 times a day, iron supplements daily, an autoimmune shot every 10 days, and a special diet that controls his allergies. He remains sweet and loving and very playful with most other dogs. He does tend to guard his yard and person so needs an adopter with Rottweiler experience and one who is prepared to continue his health routine.

Boris is so ready and deserving of his forever home. If you are that person, please contact us at FCIAadoptions@aol.com for more information.

As we are currently not having any adoption events, we are asking interested people to please fill out our application at www. FCIAnimals.org and if it looks like a good match, we will arrange an introduction.

We suggest a home with children over the age of 10 for this dog. This dog cannot be adopted out of state. Please see our home page for a list of our Saturday adoption sites. Every potential adopter is required to fill out an adoption application and the dog is placed in the home that would be most suitable for the dog. We do not place our dogs in homes with unfenced swimming pools. Generally, we don't release the dogs at the adoption site that day except on occasion to former adopters.

animal.description:
Maria - approx one year old. Must have other dog in the home. Kids over 12. Timid girl.

Meet Maria! This cutie came to us after being found roaming in the outskirts of Yakima. She was very scared and clearly unsocialized with people. She was found with her sister Mitzi.

Both girls are still quite shy with people and anyone who falls in love with them needs to understand that they still need to work on building confidence. They love their foster family but meeting strangers is still a challenge. They are especially wary of men. We prefer to see them in a female-only home.

They do not have a lot of experience walking on leashes just yet, so that is something that will need to be worked on. They go in and out of the doggy door in their foster home and love zooming around the yard together. Mitzi and Maria can be placed separately but must have another small friendly dog in the home that they can live with. They will not do well as only dogs.

Maria is a young pup with everything that comes with that - she likes to play all day long, shred toys and snuggle.

The girls have been vaccinated and microchipped and spayed.

Their adoption fee is $395. Applications to savinggreatanimals.org

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
**I'm currently in a foster home. Submit an adoption application online at www.moaspets.com/adoptionapp, and our Program Coordinator will set up a meet and greet!** Foster update: ""I have had Araina for a few weeks now, and she has gone through a beautiful transformation during that time. First and foremost, this lady is now referred to as Reina, the Spanish word for Queen, because that is exactly who she is! As a spry senior - she knows herself, what she wants, and what she likes - simple as that. Reina is independent, self-sufficient, and just needs a warm, loving home that honors her wishes. Those wishes include: - Daily walks - of course, she will let you know when her schedule allows. She is, however, willing to rearrange prior commitments for walks in the woods. - Visits to the dog park a few times a week - obviously, she alerts when she is tired of all the commoners and wants to retire to her own chambers. - Car rides - all the car rides, with open windows. Note: she simply adores the front seat. Like any queen, Reina has a heart of gold, but you may have to be patient as you work to gain her trust. She keeps a close inner circle, appearing as shy, skittish, and untrusting at first. She is aware of her royal status and is not the first to come running up for pets and love, but when you gain her trust, and she finally surrenders to your attempts at affection, it makes it all worthwhile. Reina has made an excellent guest at my home. She can be left alone without being crated (though she is crate trained) and has not touched anything in the house. Being fully house trained, Reina uses a dog door here but will alert you by sitting at the door if she needs to go outside. She is dog friendly to respectful dogs and currently lives with fellow seniors, a black lab, and a heeler. Our Queen has been tested with younger dogs as house guests and does well with them, removing herself when they get in her face too much. She has been kid-tested with children as young as 6, and I think she would do well with older kids 10+ who can respect her boundaries. Reina still has a zest for life in her and would do well with a home that can provide daily exercise, 30 minutes to an hour, for her. She does well at the dog park, and after a few minutes on a leash while walking, settles without pulling. Other than that, Reina loves to hang out on the couch - she is a great Netflix buddy, WFH colleague, and the best package delivery announcer. She is just the right mix of chill and active, loving but not a velcro dog, and would make any home happy with her little woofs throughout the day."" Ariana was an owner surrender and every time she in out in the yard, she runs to the fence to look in the parking lot. She is convinced her owner is coming back. But what she doesn't know is that one day one of those cars is going to take her to her new home. She hasn't settled in here yet, but she is coming around. She is happy to show off her tricks in the meantime, to keep us humans entertained. We are seeing more and more of her personality. She is a smart and very loyal companion. In testing her with other dogs, we learned that she might be happy with other dogs that also like to mind their own business and won't get in her space uninvited. -----
Please call the shelter at (706) 795-2868 to schedule a meet and greet. Madison Oglethorpe Animal Shelter is a non-profit shelter serving over 720 square miles. We are open intake, meaning we can not turn away animals from either county we serve. Our shelter intakes double or triple it's capacity every month so it is essential we place animals quickly into adoptive homes. Since so many animals enter the shelter we often don't have enough volunteers to write an individual bio for each. Please feel free to call the shelter Wednesday-Sunday to inquire about the animal you are interested in. 706-795-2868. Viewing and adoption hours at our shelter are Wednesday through Sunday from 12 PM to 5 PM. All adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, flea treatment, deworming, and spay or neuter, microchip, and adoption packet. Fees: Dogs over 4 months old: $100 Puppies under 4 months: $125. Cats and Kittens are $75 ($65 without microchip). For your convenience you can fill out an adoption application for any of our current residents at www.moaspets.com. Join us on Facebook at https://www.facebook.com/moaspets. It's a great way to stay up to the minute on the furry 4 legged friends we have looking for a loving forever home. We are located at: 1888 Colbert Danielsville Rd Danielsville, GA 30633 706-795-2868 NOTE: Our adoptions are first come first served, simply filling out an application does not mean the animal will be held for you, you must come meet the animal in person in order to be considered for adoption. If you rent you must bring your lease or a letter from your landlord stating you may adopt.

animal.description:
ALL adoptions require a completed application, vet check, home check and final contract.  The application to adopt can be found at www.camorescue.com.

Herbie and Henry were rescued from a terrible hoarding situation.  They are very timid at first but Henry warms up very fast.  Neither one of them bite or snap but they are just needing time to trust.  They are so cute and very bonded.  Herbie is 4 pounds and about 8 years old.  Henry is a lot more outgoing and comes to me for affection after just having them a few days.  He is very protective of Herbie and will lay on him to protect him.   Henry is about 9 pounds and 7 years old.  

Both dogs are neutered, up to date on shots, hw negative and microchipped.  Their fee is $550 for the pair. You can also read more about us here: https://www.thepupblog.com/post/meet-henry-herbie

Adoption fees are variable. Up to date vaccines, microchip, spay/neuter are included in the fee.

Once your application has been approved, we will put you in touch with the foster to set up a  meet and greet. We are a foster based RESCUE, not a shelter. All of our dogs are in individual foster homes. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We select the best applicant for each dog, based on the dog's needs. 
For the safety of our small breed dogs and based on our past experiences, we will not place our dogs in homes with large breed dogs.    

CAMO rescue is a 501c3 whose primary focus is rescuing small dogs from the euthanasia list from high kill TX shelters.   
EIN # is 46-5486022
We rescue 800+ animals a year.

Follow us on Facebook at www.facebook.com/camorescue

Our donation link is http://www.paypalme/camorescue 

We are strictly volunteer based, no salaries are paid and 100% of donations go towards rescuing dogs.

animal.description:
Please read our adoption requirements at http://gsrne.org/requirements-for-adopting-from-gsrne before contacting us about this dog.
Harvey was rescued by a lovely single Mom of two young children who found her wandering when she was visiting family down south. Harvey’s original family was located but told the young Mom they didn’t want her anymore because she kept running away. She came back to Massachusetts but, unfortunately after a few months was too much for the resident older female dog in the home. It was very hard for this family to give Harvey up —they loved her very much especially the younger 5 year old child but, knew their first priority was their own older female dog. Harvey is shy and a bit timid when you first meet her but, warms up quickly. She’s a ball of energy and is being fostered by a family with a young teenage boy. They have become best friends! She is absolutely adorable with a very sweet personality — a dog that definitely wants to please her people.

Her foster home has been working with a trainer on her obedience training. Harvey tends to be timid when she is meeting other people and other dogs.  They are working on polite greeting behavior —like many puppies her age she will sometime jump up to greet people. She does not typically bark at other dogs when she is on walks or when they pass her house.  Her foster family has been also taking her to doggy day care a few times a week for playtime and socialization where she gets along very well with the other pups. Harvey is adorable!  She is sweet, smart, and very active!  She would do well in a home with a family that will continue to work on her training and have time for lots of walks and play.

animal.description:
Looks like: Chihuahua Terrier
Male, 10 years old, 13 pounds

Pupperoni is a wiggly and spunky little boy who is very excited to meet his forever people! He loves people and other dogs and shows his excitement by jumping around to let you know he's ready to make a new friend. Once that excitement has passed, Pupperoni is a pretty mellow guy. He enjoys short walks and is a bit slow, but with encouragement excels! He is polite around other dogs, sniffing them to say hello. Pupperoni does not mind being alone and uses that time to take refreshing naps. He loves to chew and his favorite toys are scented bone-shaped ones that let him indulge in chewing as much as possible. 

Pupperoni enjoys being in the company of his person and will wake out of a deep sleep if his person leaves the room. He will sit in your lap if you sit on the floor with him and gives you little endearing finger kisses that will melt your heart. 

Pupperoni came to with little bumps all over his body that turn out to be caused by a virus called canine viral papillomatosis. He is currently being treated with an antiviral therapy, and this should resolve by mid-January or earlier. Until the lesions clear up, Pupperoni is contagious to other dogs. Once his lesions are resolved, he will no longer be contagious and he should have lifelong immunity to the virus. This virus is not contagious to people. 

Pupperoni is a good-natured boy, but if you accidentally touch a sore spot, he does nip a little and lets you know that is not a good place for him to be touched. 

Pupperoni has a heart of gold and is a low maintenance, loving dog who is ready to find his forever home! 

Pupperoni came to us from San Jose Animal Care and Services..

animal.description:
Hello!  First,Thank you for looking to adopt not shop!  I know Emma is really cute but she is a lot more then cute...she has a lot of baggage and here is a list of requirements for her adoption if you do not fall into all of these categories please do NOT reach out....we take our adoptions very seriously and will only set Emma up for success!
Please go over the list before you proceed:
*House with fenced yard ONLY no apartments etc
*NO OTHER ANIMALS NONE ZERO 
*Must have a lot of experience with dogs, many dogs 
*Must know how to train a dog and be committed to taking to a qualified trainer for classes, a trainer like John Sparks at www.sparksk9.com a serious trainer that can actually help you with Emma

If you can say yes to the 4 requirements please read on and I look forward to working with you and finding Emma's forever home!!!!

Emma is a purebred horsecoat 5 year old Chinese Shar Pei.    She found herself very neglected the past couple of years until finally her owner surrendered her so she could find a forever home that could treat her properly like a Lil Princess.

Emma is on the small side weighed in at 30 pounds but should be closer to 40 pounds max......she missed many meals as her owner forgot she existed most days.  She is great in the car and did well at the vet.  She is very food motivated so she persuades easily with a treat!

She is crate trained and is okay on a leash.  She is dying for affection.  She has beautiful eyes and coat so no allergies or entropion needed.  She is not cat friendly or dog friendly.  She needs a very dog savvy dog experienced person that is willing to take the time to train her so she finally has direction in her life.

If you are interested in adopting Miss Emma you will NOT find her or any MEOW dog at our cat shelter.  ALL Meow dogs are located in foster homes.  Please email Kelly at K9WRINKLES@AOL.COM   She can provide you with an application....after approval a home visit is set up.  Adoption fee is $175.00.
Thank you for looking to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
These pictures do not do beautiful 4 year old Chanel justice, because she is so pretty! Chanel was owned but surrendered by her owner to a shelter in Texas. She sat there since early July, and we rescued her in September along with a dozen dogs from our Texas shelter partners. 
She is quiet and shy, more shy with men initially, but so friendly. She really blossoms after a minute of baby talk, and her tail wags so fast it is so adorable. 
Her foster mom recently had her brother and a male friend over and at first here was about 5 minutes of barking, then treats, followed by tail wags and peace!

She loves to offer you her paws and give kisses. She also really likes to play fetch with squeaky toys! Chanel walks great on a leash and is not dog reactive at all, she pays them no mind or is friendly. She definitely wants to chase squirrels, though! However even that desire has subsided as she has grown more relaxed in her foster home. 

Chanel has been lucky enough to score a lovely foster home where she is enjoying lounging, quiet walks, and lots of love. 

Her foster mom writes, "Miss Chanel loves bully sticks, squeaky toys, playing fetch, and lots and lots of treats! She also loves walks and seems very interested in the squirrels when she sees them. Her favorite thing to do is to sleep before she gets the zoomies and bounces from couch to couch. Getting her belly scratched is her favorite thing and she'll even put her one paw on you to tell you to continue. 

Chanel doesn't like loud noises so would do best in a quiet home in a quiet neighborhood. 

Chanel is housebroken, but likes to be on a schedule. She likes routine! She is also very sensitive to loud noises so if there is a lot going on outside she won't relax enough to go potty on her walks. When she goes some place new she will need reassurance that outside is ok and nothing will hurt her, and this will come in time just as it has for us. Since we have had her quite a few weeks she is so much better. She is really coming into her own and is the most loving dog, she is such a delight. 

Chanel does not have any separation anxiety. Chanel has free roam of the house and every time we've returned the house looks just the same as we had left it. She's actually usually sleeping when we get home!

Chanel is a shy and quiet girl until something startles her, and then she'll get a bit barky so needs to be calmed down. Since she's so timid, it's sometimes hard to introduce her to new people, as she is so scared, especially with men. However, after a proper introduction she does great. Within minutes of baby talk and treats she is giving kisses,

But overall, even with her quirks, she really is the best dog."

Not every dog is just dumb and happy all the time, and the dogs who have quirkier personalities like Chanel deserve a home as well, because they make great and loyal companions!

Her fosters would love to tell you more about this pretty girl, so please consider doing an application today if you have a quiet home, outside of the city, and love and patience to give.

Chanel is Heartworm positive but her case is very mild, so we are treating it using the slow kill method. Chanel will continue to have a normal quality of life throughout her treatment and we will treat her until she tests negative. Heartworm is not contagious to dogs or people, and it is preventable, and it is also curable. We treat at no cost to an adopter, they just come in once every two months to pick up medication. 

Please do not let this deter you from considering this mellow, beautiful pink-spotted marshmallow of a dog! She is so deserving of a forever home! 

Chanel's adoption fee has been generously sponsored too! Please apply today!

animal.description:
GOOD with dogs, GOOD with kids, GOOD with cats

ADOPTION FEE: $400 www.unbreakabull.com/adopt

Victory! My name is Kai, and I have been victorious in healing from a medical condition that nearly cost me my life. I got into something that I wasn’t supposed to eat and it caused an obstruction inside. I was getting sick, but it wasn’t understood why. When I went to the vet, it was discovered that I had a bowel obstruction and would need surgery to release it. I had the surgery, and after my recovery time, I am ready to go! I am 1 yr and 8 months old, and I am just the happiest little man on the planet! I see the joy in a second chance at life. I love being around other dogs, I have no issues with cats, and I am learning to be calm around kids because I truly am still just a puppy. I absolutely love going on walks, and I do great on a leash. I will play fetch in the yard, but I’m not too keen on bringing the ball back. I don’t want to do all the work you know. Due to being a puppy, I am still a bit mouthy, but we are working on that, and I am getting the hang of it. I don’t bark, and I am house and crate trained. I love chewing on my bones and playing with my toys, and I am not aggressive with them. I am going to need someone that is firm, yet loving, because I am still learning the ropes of being a puppy, so I still have some teaching and learning that needs to be done. I am a puppy in a bigger boy body, but I am sweet as can be. I am looking for my forever home, and I am hoping that it could be you!! I want to continue to be victorious, and I think that you could be my perfect match, so if you feel the same, please head over and fill out an application to take me home!! Until I hear from you, I am going to work on this whole fetch thing because apparently it’s my job to bring the ball back when it’s thrown; who knew. Love, Kai (UPDATED 01/20/21

animal.description:
Thibodeaux is forever home ready and CANNOT WAIT!
Thibodeaux is a lab mix born in May 2020 and is currently around 35 pounds. He will be large fully grown; around 60-70 pounds. 
He was the baby of two dumped dogs who had a quick fling and made a cute lil thing!
Thibodeaux is all puppy, he loves playing with any new friends and thinks everyone is his best friend. It takes him a day or so to warm up to people as he had a more isolated start, but with more socialization and experiences his confidence will continue to grow. He absolutely LOVES giving kisses to his friends and loves his belly rubbed. He has so much potential as the smart boy he is, and he is ready to please! 
With the cutest pink nose, golden eyes and chestnut fur on the tips of his ears, how can you say no?

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about are animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (1 application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for puppies covers initial deworming,  puppy vaccinations, microchip, and spay/neuter at the rescue's approved vet at 6 months of age. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

I absolutely love affection, belly scratches, neck scratches - you name it and I’m game. I’m also game for outdoor activities. There are some really great parks in the local area that I’ve visited with some of the great volunteers at PAC. I enjoy taking in all the sites, smells and trails, so I can go for a couple of miles if you’re up for it!

When not out on trails, I’m interested in mental stimulation too if you have a puzzle mat I can play with! I’m young – only around 11 months old – so my positive energy needs multiple avenues to explore. Even though I’m young, I’m already pretty good with this whole potty-training thing. I know, right? I pat myself on the back for that one!

Even though I’ll miss the lovely staff and volunteers, I’m ready to have a family of my own! I could likely live with the right doggy pal, and I would do best in a cat-free home with kiddos 10 years or older. Hmmm, maybe I like their toys too much. Anyway, are you ready for me to join your family? Just go here (https://providenceac.org/AdoptADog) and set up an appointment to meet me! I’m in one of the first kennels, so you can’t miss me. I’m the one with the big pointy ears and beautiful caramel colored coat...and there's a good chance I'll be reaching out to hold your hand, too.

XO Ru Paw

P.S. I'm all set to move-in - already neutered, microchipped & up to date on vaccinations. 

P.S.S. I almost forgot the BIG NEWS: A generous donor is eager to help me find my forever home, so they have sponsored my adoption fee! That means I can join your family today for FREE! YAY!"


-------
During your appointment, you will be able to meet a selection of pets in the Kennels or Cattery that day. New pets are arriving daily!
-------

Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. 

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

animal.description:
My name is Liam, but I go by Sans, and I’m 3 year old male smaller Australian Shepherd weighing about 45 pounds. Im fully potty and crate trained, I walk well on the leash, and I know fun tricks like sit, shake, high five, and lay down. 

I absolutely love to play with other dogs and would like a forever home with a play buddy for me. I’ve unfortunately not been around cats yet, so I’m not sure if I like them or not. 

My ideal family would have no children around and not too many frequent visitors as meeting new people makes me pretty anxious, but I am working on it and getting better every day. I’d love a family that is patient and understanding of my unknown past trauma that has made meeting new humans a fearful experience initially. My foster parents have been working on new techniques with me to feel more comfortable meeting people and it has helped a lot. I’ve made a lot more human friends than I ever thought I’d like and I’m now ready to meet my furever family. 

I do require a home with a fully fenced in yard and would not do well in a condo/apartment. 

If you would like to meet me, please fill out an application at www.speakfortheunspoken.com/adopt

All dogs are fostered throughout the Puget Sound area and are brought to the events where they can be met by prospective adopters. Additional pictures of adoptable dogs can be seen at: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/photos_stream?tab=photos_albums. animal.description:
Meet Frisco! Frisco is one of about 50 dogs rescued from a neglectful hoarding situation in South Georgia back in early July. Some of the dogs on the property had been living inside and were more socialized, able to be adopted quickly. But sadly, there was another group that had lived their whole lives outside with little human interaction. It has taken a couple of months of living in a foster home for them to start realizing that there are good people in this world who will love and cherish them. These dogs have come amazingly far since being rescued but do still carry the weight of their previous life with them. As such, they have very specific adoption requirements listed below. Please understand, we have taken 3 months to get to know these dogs and what they need to succeed. The adoption requirements are not arbitrary but are what is needed for them to lead happy, healthy lives and as such no exceptions to these requirements will be allowed. 

 

Frisco is about a year and a half old and under 25 lbs. Hes a sweet, playful boy but still a bit on the shy side. He needs a patient adopter who is going to give him the time and space he needs to adjust and get comfortable in a new home. Given that the best teachers for dogs lacking confidence are other dogs, Frisco also must have other confident dogs in the home with at least one of them being under 30 lbs and playful. He is learning to walk on a leash but has yet to gain enough confidence to go to the bathroom on leash and does require a SECURELY fenced yard - solid wood privacy fence only (minimum 6 ft); chain link, wrought iron, or other types of fencing are not sufficient. Lastly, given that Frisco is still learning to trust people, he will not do well with the unpredictable nature of children. He is still somewhat fearful of men but could possibly learn to trust a quiet, patient man in the home if his primary caretaker is a woman 

 

We do understand that the above requirements greatly narrows the pool of potential adopters and may even scare some people away. Frisco is most definitely a work in progress but we cannot even begin to explain how rewarding it is to watch the transformation of a dog like this who has never known love before. Once they learn to love and trust, they are so very very grateful and the amount of love they have to give and their loyalty knows no bounds. If you are interested in becoming part of Friscos continuing story, email adrienne@rescuemega.org or fill out an adoption application on our website- www.rmgdogs.org

animal.description:
6mo. old. Sweet boy. 

Here is a bio from his previous home:

"The best way to describe Crosby is to tell you about a day in his life.

In the morning, we go out a greet the two of them in their enclosed area. Of course, both are happy to see us. They go out in our backyard to take care of business and then return to the house. Crosby’s morning routine is to climb up, with assistance, into my lap and get his morning hugs and kisses. He loves this time and enjoys every moment of this. They will have breakfast and then it’s off to our morning walk. We have found walking them separately has worked best. I walk Crosby. He loves his walks.  He’s still learning to manage himself during our walk. At times, he will bark at other people or dogs as we walk by. Some walks he does great other times he needs a little help to get through it. I’ve found if I keep moving forward with him, he will move on to the next thing. After our walk, he will come back home and play with his toys or brother (when things weren’t as intense) and then settle in for a morning nap. He will at times go off and find his own space and snuggle in. At other times, he’ll want to snuggle with someone while he sleeps. 

After his nap, he usually likes to head outside. It nice that we have a dog door in our screened in pool, so when he wakes he can go out on his own. If the sliding doors are closed he’ll paw at the door and let us know he wants to go out. He loves getting attention playing with one of his toys or will run around the backyard. After a light lunch, it is usually back to sleep for another nap. We he gets up it’s time for our afternoon walk and more play. This will continue until dinner time. After dinner it’s sleeping time (this is when he really likes to snuggle). He gets up and times plays a little bit, heads out to take care of business, and then come in for a night’s sleep.

Crosby is a handsome dog (people will comment about him on walks). He gets really excited when people come to the house. We are working on his level of excitement (staying down instead of jumping up). Of the two of them, he is more intimated by his brother. At times, we have to coax him in from outside when his brother, Nash, stands out on the deck. We will be in between the two of them and walk in with Crosby. 

 More Info:

Crosby loves to love you, kisses abundant ! Always wanting to sit/lie on or with you to watch tv- or nap.  He loves your company but also can be independent as he likes to nap when your busy and will enjoys stretching out.  Remember he is a puppy and loves to chew!
 
Has learned to sit and wait before eating kibble.  He takes a prompt from being given a handful of kibble and then will proceed to eat on his own. 

Enjoys playing with you using his toys for tug of war,  or having gentle ball play, and greeting people!   He is friendly and likes to talk often barking or making stretch noises to communicate what he wants or giving thanks.

Although he enjoys walks, he can be lay back and just hangout.  Two of his favor treats are large carrots and medium size dream bones!

Crosby learns best with repetition and treats for performing the right behavior.  He is learning more each day on short walks with treats for good behavior.

We will bring all paper work from the Vet for Crosby with us, as well as his favorite things. We are heartbroken but feel it’s best for him. He’s a handsome boy and very loving which should make him very attractive to potential families. If you need more pictures let me know and I can forward them to you.


Fee is 300

animal.description: It was an absolutely perfect Ozark afternoon for a Humane Society dog to have the chance to frolic in the bark park. 2-year-old Aggie took advantage of his opportunity and dashed about the park with wonderful abandon. He is a handsome, powerfully built, playful canine who shares lots of smiles with his human friends. When Aggie decided to take a break, he hopped into the “doggie pool” and put his head under water in search of an occasionally mis-tossed treat. Aggie has been working with a Humane Society volunteer and will now repeatedly perform a sit on request and is being taught to remain in that position till released. He is still a puppy (a rather large one) at heart and has some work to do on developing better manners. One of his current talents is the innate ability to make you feel comfortably protected and secure. As are most Rottweiler’s, he is confident and courageous with a self-assured persona. He confided to the photographer that despite his name, he is in reality a true fan of the Razorbacks. He also shared that he isn’t overly impressed with a certain A & M Collie mascot. As you would expect, Aggie’s mascot role model is none other than Tusk V.

animal.description:
Sue, was surrendered to a local vets office. After spending quite some time waiting for the right family, we offered our assistance. 
Suki is a 3 year old, healthy American Bulldog mix. She loves people and needs a calm home with an experienced owner. She gets along well with others but does have some food aggression therefore food and treats should be closely monitored. 

 American Bulldogs are known for being loyal, inquisitive dogs with outgoing personalities and affectionate dispositions. Suki is a sweet girl and a survivor. She was deprived of the training she needed as a pup. 
 She is ready for a person or entire family to love. In foster care, Suki is decompressing and learning she deserves to be comfortable.  Suki is housebroken, intelligent, and loves opportunities to be 
outside with her people. She has been around teenage boys and lots of women . 
Cats could be questionable. . She has been wonderful with a male dog but will not tolerate anyone close to her food . 

If you are a match for Suki and interested in giving her a forever home, email RescueHeartsAlabama@gmail.com for more information. Fenced yard and vet information is required .

animal.description:
Buddy came to our rescue because his former owner decided to dump him at a gas station. He didn't take him to the shelter or make an effort to rehome him, but rather opened the car door and set him loose in a high traffic area. A good samaritan was at the gas station that day and, fortunately for Buddy, she made sure he could experience the better side of humanity that day. She brought him home and started asking for help, which is how Buddy ended up with us.

According to this good sam, Buddy didn't actually have a name. The owner dumping him had never bothered to give him one, which is surprising when you consider that he's totally potty trained and crate trained, well-socialized, and a year old. Buddy is incredibly loving, dog and kid friendly, and one of the easiest fosters we've had. He would not be a good friend to cats in the home and he needs a 6 foot fence (the boy can jump!). Applications without physical fences cannot be considered.

Being dumped was ultimately the best thing that could have happened to Buddy. He has gone from nameless and abandoned to loved and ready for a family that will adore him. And it's so easy to do. He lives with his best friend and wrestle-buddy, Odin, who is also available for adoption through RESCUEDohio (check out his page if you're interested in adopting both!). Buddy would do best with a doggie playmate. He would do best in a home with a family who can continue to introduce him to people by practicing his calm "sit" and re-directing him when he jumps due to excitement. He loves people.

Buddy is most likely a lab/hound mix and estimated at 6 months to 1 year old. He is around 70lbs. If you're an approved applicant and would like to meet Buddy, please email your adoption coordinator or info@rescuedohio.org. To become an adopter, please apply at rescuedohio.org. Buddy's adoption fee is $300.

This big girl is Princess.  She is two years old and weighs 63 lbs. 

She comes off a little stuck up - she pays attention to you if she wants to and if she doesn't she is excellent at ignoring you.  When she wants your attention she is very sweet.  She definitely has a mind of her own.She is housebroken and good with male dogs.  We have no cat informaton on her.  We do not recommend her with small children.

We can warn you that she does not like a crate - she destroyed one on her tirp home from the vet's office with total ease.  She also is very smart and figured out how to use a chair in the exercise yard to clear our 6' fence.  She can't jump a 6' fence but give her the aid of a chair and she is over it with ease.

She won't be able to start looking for a forever home until probably the end of January - she has been diagnosed with Hip Dysplasia in both hips and surgeries are scheduled.

She is spayed, current on shots and has been heartworm treated.  She is current on her preventatives.  If you are the pack leader this girl needs please go to our website and complete an adoption application - www.patriotsforpets.com   visitors are only allowed with pre-approved applications.  Her adoption fee will be $250.00.

Ringo is looking for his "Strawberry Fields Forever" home. This Starr is a fun, short-legged big pup who adores people and loves to cuddle! He seems to do well with most other dogs once introduced, and takes his social cues from other well-socialized dogs. "A Day in the Life" of Ringo would include short walks and learning new things. Ringo appears to be house-trained and is learning to use a crate. He's a playful guy who just wants to have fun and enjoy life! Ringo will make a wonderful companion in a home with teens and adults after a few handling sessions to ensure the right match. "Come Together" today with Ringo and make history. Remember, "All You Need is Love" and Ringo is just the pup to deliver!

If you are interested in meeting Ringo go to la.bestfriends.org/adopt and fill out our Dog Adoption Survey and our team will reach out to you!

animal.description:
Please read entire posting for information on our new procedures. We are currently requiring appointments for all adoptions.  Please give us a call if you questions about a pet or complete an application at https://adoptmountainpets.org/pet-services/adoption-process/application-form to make arrangements to visit the Animal Resource Center.

Peach is a very unfortunate  story as are many of our dogs right now.  It may be early to post her she has been here at the shelter for a very very long time and we want to at least begin to introduce them to idea of finding the loving family she deserves.  
When Peach came to us she could not be touched, did not know what a leash was and was terrified to be inside. 
 Both have made tremendous progress and Peach will now walk on leash with her favorite people and approach slowly and take treats.    She ahs never been anything but sweet but is just so shy. 
We know opening your home to girl like Peach is a big ask and long shot but we are not going to give up on her... She is very loving once she gets used to you! She loves to run around and play with other dogs!  We are hoping for a home with another more confident dog for Peach to follow around. 
Peach will likely never be an off leash dog and will be best in home with a fenced yard.  


Adopters will be considered on the totality of the application and how it matches the particular pet's needs.


Most dogs who come from the shelter will not be house trained.

We do not know or make guarantees that a dog or cat will do well with all children, other animals or is house-trained.

We will need to talk to all of the adults in the home prior to making an appointment to visit with a pet. 

In most cases its necessary to to have family dogs come into meet your potential adoptee. Please be sure your dogs are spayed or neutered and current on vaccines (distemper - parvo and rabies) before bringing them for a meeting.

All dogs must be transported home in a travel crate to transport your new pup home safely.

Renters must provide a copy of a lease indicating pets are allowed or contact information for the landlord.


Second Chance is happy to have been providing stray, surrender, adoption, and our Community Outreach services throughout the COVID situation.   

All services are provided by appointment only.  Please do not visit the shelter without first making calling the shelter. 

For the safety of our community, staff and volunteers all visitors are required to wear masks and follow the posted social distancing processes *see below.  Do not make an appointment if you are not comfortable following these procedures.  Thank you for understanding and your support.  

If you are interested in meeting or adopting one of our pets or have questions about the process please see our website at www.adoptmountainpets.org or call the Shelter between 11:00 am and 5:45 pm Tuesday through Saturday. 970 626 2273

*  We want to provide you excellent customer service today and keep you and our team safe and healthy. Please read what we are asking you to do today to reduce the risk of spreading COVID-19:

• Maintain a distance of at least 6 feet from other people. Six feet is the average length of many dog leashes but handing a leashes to another person is not maintaining a six foot space.
• Follow staff instructions about how to drop off, pick up or meet a pet.
• If you have any symptoms of illness please reschedule.
• Wear a mask when interacting with staff
• Wash your hands or use hand sanitizer (you can find bottles throughout the property prior to interacting with staff, volunteers or pets.
• Once you have read these guidelines, please tell us you understand them and that you will follow them with at SCHS.
Thank you for your support, for adopting, for fostering and volunteering and understanding our need to do our part in stopping COVID – 19.

animal.description:
Please welcome island girl Cora!
This sweet little girl were struggling to survive on the streets as a scared stray little puppy in the Dominican Republic.
A great Samaritan that locally comes to the aid of dogs in need on her island. Took these girls in an contacted rescues in the states for help.
We answered the call and we flew in these girl and many others.
It is now Cora's turn to find her forever home.
She is about 1yrs old. Fully trained. With housebreaking and learning all her commands and household manners.

Cora fosters with her great foster daddy and i learning so much and is areal joy! 
She is learning the ropes everyday.

. Cora is fully housebroken and crate trained and is learning her manners too,  Cora would  like a normal suburb home away from the city and loud noises and traffic. Cora Prefers to be the only furkid in her home! She loves to play with pups outside her home at parks and play dates, but in her home she doesn't want to share her Mom/ Dad or her personal space. Can you Blame her? 

You have to to understand these were once street dogs being hit by cars and abused by public kids and poisoned, to then finding rescue with a nice lady on the beach, to Now here in the States with big city noise and such, so lets gives this girl some Peace again! She can still be alittle shyy with new meets and new things but she gets better every day, every week!

Must haves for Cora:

Dog experienced owners, willing to continue the good work our foster dad has done and make Cora a great success story. 
Cora will do best in a single person home. She bonds with her 1 human to trust for direction, control and affection. she has a hard time trusting more then her 1 person and has proven little tough in a multi family home. 
so Cora would make a great attention to that 1 person to give her a chance! 



If you would like to be Cora's hero please email us for an application and Come meet her!
Hemlockedgerescue@yahoo.com

animal.description:
This absolutely precious blue Pit Bull is THE sweetest little Pittie around!  She looks brown in some of these pictures, but she is really a beautiful, rich gray color.   BABY was found in a deep, watery ditch guarding an old pizza box that she had already licked down to the cardboard!
Baby is just that... a young, sweet, innocent little girl who needs a good home with lots of love and play to share!  She is about 2 years old, weighs approx 50 pounds and has been fully vaccinated, spayed, and microchipped!  She tested heartworm-Negative and has been receiving regular heartworm prevention.  Baby is both crate and house-trained!  She does not enjoy stormy weather, but she doesn't pace or drool.  She just gets in a close, tight space and waits for it to pass.  She has her own Thundershirt in bright pink, and she happily stands still while you put it on her.  She knows it makes her feel better.  ?
This sweetheart is a happy, energetic little girl who loves to ride in the car, play fetch, and is a pro at catching a single kibble in the air!   She hasn't been tested with cats, but by the way she stalks and chases squirrels, I wouldn't risk it.  But, there is No exaggeration when I say that this little Pit is a total lover!  If you think you would like to spend a bunch of years having fun and cuddling with this little girl, please apply for her today!  Complete the application you will find in the upper left portion of the homepage of our website, www.BaytownHumaneSociety.org

animal.description: This red boy came to his foster home just before Christmas, so he is called Santa’s Little Helper, or “Santa” for short his racing name was JA’a Costal). At two years old he is still very puppy like and will collect and play with toys, especially ones that squeak. He is very energetic and will run through the house skidding on throw rugs or turn laps in the back yard. Toys and shoes will be collected, but he has not chewed up anything. He is on the vocal end of the spectrum for a greyhound and will bark quite easily, and tends to whine if he is shut out of the room his people are in. A good bond will be formed with his family, but he is fearful of new people. However, he will warm up and trust them if they are nice to him. He walks well on a lead, rides well in a car, and found out he loves camping. Santa is an energetic puppy like boy who is a little skittish but loves his people.

animal.description:
Castella is a funny and sweet girl who is happy and loves to play.  She’s a bit shy initially but once she knows you’re nice, she’s all over you.  She is house trained, crate trained, and ready to play with a furry sibling!  

If you are interested in pursuing an adoption and you live in Texas , please complete the application (links provided below). The process includes a vet check, calling references and doing a home visit. 

http://www.texassleddogrescue.org/web_documents/tsdr_application.pdf
or
https://www.formstack.com/forms/?1632205-WX2Zb144ZP

Please note the following:
We rarely do out of state adoptions.  (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience and will require same adoption process.)
Children in the home or that visit often must be at least 6 years of age. (Exceptions can be discussed but will be based on previous big dog experience.)
Adoption donation is due at the time of adoption.  Puppies under 1 year are $300. Dogs 1 year to 7 years are $200 and dogs over 7 years are $150.  As this is a donation, it will be non-returnable if dog is returned to rescue.
Dogs are not placed on a "first come, first serve" basis but rather the best home for the dog. 
All dogs placed by TSDR will be:
spayed/neutered
vaccinated for distemper/parvo, rabies, and bordetella
heartworm tested and treated if needed
microchipped
other vetting as deemed needed
New owners will receive copies of all available vet information and must agree to keep them current on all of the above.

animal.description:
Yoda, I am! And the Force is definitely strong with me. I've been through some tough times, but TLP and my foster mom never gave up. Now I'm stronger and healthier than ever, and ready to find my forever home, I am!

When I say I love to be with people, I mean I looooove to be with people. I especially enjoy short walks (I get SO excited about walks) and long car rides! My favorite spot is right by the door or window, where I can watch all the goings-on of the neighborhood. 

I'm dog-friendly, too! I'm a big guy and I take playing seriously. Just make sure to watch me so I don't overdo it! I haven't been around cats, but I am totally unmoved to chase squirrels and other critters in the yard. That's too much energy for me!! I'd rather be taking a nap or chomping on my toys.

Since I came to TLP in May, I've had a few tumors removed and knee surgeries. But now I'm recovered and ready to go! I'm going through treatment for heartworms and my cropped ears are susceptible to ear infections. TLP can talk you through my care and how to keep me in tip-top shape.

I'm the happy, affectionate boy you're looking for. Just throw me in the backseat and let's ride off into the sunset. Apply to meet me now!

Ivy is an adorable and petite 2 year old black lab / spaniel mix. She is about 50 pounds so she looks like a miniature lab and has a forever puppy face, she is beyond cute! She wags her tail so much when she sees people who might give her some pets and love! She is a smart cookie and is already learning her basic commands. Ivy was rescued from a high kill shelter in Mexico, where she was at risk due to space. She is so grateful to be out and loves to be around her humans! She walks very well on a leash- although she likes to sniff all the bushes and trees, she hardly pulls and is easy to walk! Ivy also appears to be house trained as she has not had a single accident in the house! If you would like to meet Ivy please submit an application on CodysFriendsRescue.com She has completed 30 days of training and ready to roll! Ivy is looking for an energetic home filled with love, goodness, and friendship. She is ready and raring for activities that keep her mind and body active. Ivy has gone through behavioral training and is a great dog. She is a spayed 2 yr old lab/ mix who loves being outside, going for walks, and spending time with her humans. Ivy is a wonderfully intelligent, and exuberant. This athletic girl would be a great companion for someone who enjoys staying active. Ivy is 3 years old, housebroken, and kennel trained. She finds excitement in catching treats and relishes in learning new tricks. She would enjoy doing agility training with you, learning to catch a frisbee, or just being outside spending time with you!! Come and meet this happy, bouncy, confident girl:we know you'll fall in love with her!

animal.description:
This is our girl Sabrina.  Sabrina was running stray,  Several people were monitoring her whereabouts. They would have a sighting and attempt to get close to her or call her and try tempting her with food, but were always in the end greeted with a growl, snarl, and a hasty departure. She was seen in many different locations, covering miles.  People kept seeing this large, matted, dirty dog.   A plan to use the large live trap was decided on.  The trap was set close to the last spotting.  Then came the food.  Freshly cook meat, potatoes and gravy.  Friends living close were on "dog in the trap alert".     In less than an hour the call came that the dog was indeed in the trap. Transported in the trap, we arrived at the shelter.  This poor animal was so  full of mats, burrs, dirt, mud, and poop,  we were unable to distinguish  ,whether male or female. We called the dog "Ghost."  After a getting acquainted time, we proceeded with  treats, play, and brushing.  It got to the point that brushing was appreciated and even enjoyed. It also became apparent that Ghost was not a good name for this "GIRL"  We would call her Sabrina. 

We are learning more about her every day.  She enjoys play time.  Her favorite is her red ball.  She is not at all fond of small dogs, so we are guessing that cats are on the same  level.  She seems to have taken a liking to one of the male shepherds  here. We want to express that Introduction is an absolute must if you have another dog.

Sabrina has been fully vetted, is spayed,  up to date on vaccines,  and clear  of heartworm.
We will be taking applications for her adoption.  If you have further questions about Sabrina or our adoption process you may e-mail us at echelon@airadv.net or you may also telephone the Thumb Animal Shelter at 989-375-4204.

Dog's Weight: 45 pounds

Good with small dogs?: Yes

Good with big dogs?: Yes

Good with cats?: Don't know yet

Good with kids?: Don't know yet

12/17/20:
Zoe has been with me 1 week after spending most of her 13 months in a Shelter. She is very timid and shy but she is making slow progress. She loves her crate and feels safe there. Zoe has a good appetite and loves treats. She is pretty much house trained and only had accidents at night. Her favorite thing in the world is going for a walk. She never strains at the leash and is very inquisitive. She is never aggressive when meeting other dogs. She has a pitbull next door , Daisy Duke who she has become very fond of! Gifts today from a secret Santa has peaked an interest in toys she probably never had before .More to come as this beautiful girl continues to come out of her shell!!

animal.description:
CeCe is a stunning girl who will quickly capture your heart with her wonderful smile. CeCe came to NGPR in April and gave birth to 8 beautiful puppies! She was an excellent mama to her babies and now it’s her turn to find her furever home! CeCe has excellent house manners. Even though she’s had no formal training, we think she will be quick to learn as she is eager to please and so sweet. CeCe is a bit timid in new situations and a little slow to warm up to people. Her favorite foods, cheese and whipped cream cheese are sure to help her learn to trust a bit quicker :) CeCe is nervous when she sees the leash but walks well with her pack. Speaking of a pack, she loves her canine companions and looks to them for guidance, so she would love a sibling in her new home to keep her company and show her the ropes. CeCe prefers to be wherever you are - inside or outside. She thumps her tail enthusiastically the minute she hears you coming and her infectious smile comes out when getting good pets! CeCe is an easy-going girl looking for the Pyrfect family to give her the love she deserves. If she sounds like your kind of girl, apply for CeCe today!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.
