animal.description:
Dixie Girl is waiting for some lucky person, couple, or family to adopt her.

Dixie did not have the best start in life. After she was rescued from a derelict house with 10 other dogs, she was finally taken in as a foster by a couple who works from home. They have four other dogs of their own.

Here is what her foster “mom” says about Dixie.

“Despite having four dogs, we took her as a foster because she was not doing well in the boarding kennel. Some dogs get frustrated in a short time -- she is one.”

“Dixie isn’t a cute, nervous, little pet. She is a cattle dog mix with all the best qualities of her heritage, which means she is powerful, athletic, super smart, loyal, playful, and affectionate. She is the type of dog who will be a true companion and a good buddy.”

“She gets along well with all our dogs. She plays endlessly with our young male dog. At night she sometimes sleeps with our alpha dog, a large female. Dixie competes with our two extremely needy dogs for attention, but never once has shown aggression towards either of them.”

“When Dixie Girl wants attention, she brings a tennis ball to me. And when I want attention, I ask Dixie to find the ball. She communicates game-on with another dog by waving the ball in their face.”

“She checks on me during the day by looking through the window and follows me in the yard. The highlight of her day is a walk. She is good on a leash after she calms down. She gets distracted by cats and sometimes gophers. A dog biscuit can help refocus her attention.”

“She sometimes digs. She will chase cats and critters…and she is fast. On the other hand, Dixie has never chewed the dog quilts or blankets -- unlike our male dog who eats and chews anything. Dixie does not bark impulsively as some dogs do.”

“She gets very excited when she sees me. Sometimes she jumps on me…sometimes just in front of me. I think this will stop once she isn’t competing with four other dogs for my attention. Note: our super needy dog often gets everyone jumping. When not competing with the others, Dixie often leans slightly against my legs, which is a dog-hug.”

“Dixie is more interesting than most dogs -- she learns extremely fast and enjoys the attention. Dixie Girl is a wonderful dog who I believe, with the right home, will blossom into a truly remarkable companion.”

Dixie is spayed, immunized, heartworm negative, and on heartworm preventative. She is full-grown and weighs about 60 lbs. She is a real sweetie pie. Interested in meeting Dixie? Contact Second Chance Mason Animal Rescue at 325-347-6929 or email adoptions@secondchancemason.com.

animal.description:
Luna is the most gorgeous Pyr girl - she has the long, fluffy coat that is pyrfect to snuggle against - if she trusts you enough, she may even roll over and deem you worthy to rub her belly! Luna can be a tad shy when it comes to meeting strangers, but if you are willing to give her time and space to get used to your presence, she will soon transform into the most loving girl. In fact, when she decides to put her trust in you, not only will she wag her tail furiously, but also do a silly happy dance as she can hardly contain her happiness :) Luna enjoys chilling outdoors during the day, and she loves to take long naps in her dog bed when it is time to come inside for the evening. This beautiful girl will do well with an experienced handler who is familiar with Pyrs and their behaviors, and who will continue working with her using the positive reinforcement that she responds to, surely to bring out the best in Luna!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Meet Journey! She is an approx 3 year old, 78 pound German Shepherd. GSD breed experience will be required to adopt her. She is appropriately named after volunteers tracked this beautiful female black Shepard for over six weeks after a witness saw her tossed from a truck. Injured and terrified she ran and hid and ran and hid day after day. We make note of this because this gal will need a patient owner to reduce the flight instinct that kept her alive while she was on the run. She is housebroken and crate trained but is super agile so a six foot fenced property is required for adoption. She is affectionate and bonds tightly once she trusts you as happens with her breed. She wants a family that is home a lot to spend time with her. She is good with other dogs and takes comfort from them so will require a confident dog buddy in her forever home. She plays pretty hard so no small dogs or cats to avoid accidental injury. She is good with kids who approach appropriately...scares her when they are rushing at her so looking for a home without young kids. She would be an incredible lure coursing pup or agility dog because she is so smart and driven to please.
Journey is spayed, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Her adoption donation is only $250.

To meet any of our dogs please fill out an application on www.maxxandme.org.

Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

Sweet little Lucas is a 1.5 year old, 12 pound, cream colored Chihuahua mix. He has a DAZZLING smile! This handsome boy is shy. He was brought to us by a good Samaritan who found Lucas & his sister Leia in her grape field on Lucas Rd. Leia was pregnant and delivered her pups 3 days after arriving in her foster home. He will need you to be patient with him until you earn his trust. He will need leash training and a little time to learn that car rides are fun! He loves his people time and would enjoy spending the day with you. He will sit quietly while you work from home. When he greets you he gets so happy that he JUMPS and dances with JOY. We believe he will blossom quickly in his new home. He would be fine with or without another dog in the home though he gets along great with other dogs. He is an active boy so he needs a house with a yard where he can run & play outdoors with his family. He will need some potty training, he is learning to use the doggie door. Here at the sanctuary after breakfast & dinner we use the command “Go Potty”. Lucas obeys and goes right out the door. Continue this at home and he should be potty trained quickly. Lucas has been neutered, microchipped and is current on vaccinations. Are you ready for a sweet boy to love? OFFICE

animal.description:
**WE ARE CURRENTLY DOING ADOPTIONS BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. YOU MUST CALL TO SCHEDULE AN APPOINTMENT IF YOU'RE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING. PLEASE LEAVE US A VOICEMAIL IF YOU ARE UNABLE TO REACH US. THANK YOU FOR YOUR PATIENCE AND UNDERSTANDING.- CCDP STAFF**

Hi there. My name is Olaf. I am almost 2 and I weigh about 42 lbs. 
I was surrendered to the pound after being found living neglectfully outside chained to a dog house. My owner claimed they put me outside because I had fleas...  
I am unsocialized and will require a patient new family with the time to work with me on training, socialization and housebreaking. I am very sweet once I get to know you some. 
I do not do well with other dogs and will require a home where I can be the only pet. 
If you're looking for a nice dog to add to your family, please consider adopting me.

Our adoption fee is $150.00. The pound DOES NOT accept checks for adoption fees. We're able to accept cash for adoption OR Visa/ Mastercard/ Discover Card. A convenience fee of 2.39% will be applied to all credit/ debit card adoptions. If you intend to do a foster-to-adopt, the fee must be cash. ALL dogs/puppies adopted from our shelter will receive their parvo distemper vaccine, bordetella vaccine, rabies vaccine (if aged at 12 weeks or older), be dewormed with a 3 day course of panacur dewormer, be microchipped, receive their current Ohio dog license and will be spayed or neutered. ALL DOGS/PUPPIES WILL BE SPAYED OR NEUTERED unless a health issue prohibits the surgery from being performed. Not all dogs posted for adoption are spayed/ neutered yet. If you're driving a long distance to adopt, please verify that the vetting process has been completed and dog you're interested in adopting is still available for adoption. The above mentioned vetting is all included in your adoption fee. The adoption fee and what is included in the adoption fee is NON-NEGOTIABLE.

Adoptions MUST be done at the pound and in person as there is paperwork to fill out and an adoption contract that must be signed by the adopter. This means you must be willing to travel to our shelter to adopt.

IF the dog you're interested in adopting has medical conditions or injuries which require medical treatment, we ask that you help with the medical bills so we can continue to help the dogs coming in who need additional vet care.
We are a county run shelter, therefore we cannot control our intake or the health or behavior of the dogs that come in to our shelter.

Although we try our hardest to place all of our adoptable dogs, there are certain circumstances in which any dog in our care could be euthanized at any time and without further notice (IE: sudden untreatable medical condition or injury, temperament or behavioral problems which may not be apparent when the dog first arrives, lack or space, etc.), therefore all dogs at our shelter should be considered urgent. The adoption of a more highly adoptable dog will mean more time for the less adoptable dog in the kennel next to him!

Shelter hours are: Monday-Friday: 8 am- 4 pm
Saturday: 8 am - 11 am.
Sunday: 8 am - 11 am.
Adoptions are always welcome during hours of operation. We will make special arrangements for adoptions in advance.
There is nobody in the office on Saturday and Sunday, so therefore we are unable to answer or return phone calls over the weekend.

Can't adopt a dog? We would love to have more volunteers who are able to spend time with our dogs! The dogs LOVE going for walks and the socialization and exercise helps make the dogs more adoptable.

Contact information:
8455 County Home Road
Lisbon, OH 44432
(330)424-6663

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Debbie at debbied@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Natasha
Estimated Breed : German Shepherd Mix
Approximate Age: 2 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 45 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Natasha is a gorgeous girl who is looking for a very special home who will take a chance on her. Natasha hasn't had the best experience at the beginning of her life which makes her protective of herself and her surrounding. She takes a while to warm up to new people, and will growl at first when uncomfortable and unsure. Once she settles into a home, she bonds very deeply and would give her life for her person, however, she does tend to become protective of the home and her person so would need a home that is comfortable understanding that she will need to be separated when new visitors come into the home and introduced to strangers carefully and with patience. She is extremely sweet, loyal, and protective but her protectiveness sadly make her not suitable for a home with lots of visitors or family who is looking for a social dog they can take everywhere.. We know it's a long shot for Natasha to find a home, but we are hopeful that there is a wonderful family out there who will take the time to get this diamond in the ruff to warm up, fall in love, and be loyal and give their life for them for the rest of her life. Natasha cannot live in an apartment.
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

Parker loves attention and would adore spending all day on someone’s lap.  This boy has been through the ringer!  Will you be his hero?

animal.description:
Dugan is housebroken and is learning commands of sit and wait. He has a lot of energy and would enjoy an active family. He loves to go walking/jogging. Dugan would probably do best in a home with another active dog to play with. He is cat friendly but gets overly excited. So would recommend a home with no kitties or older/mellow cats. Dugie loves toys and playing fetch or tug of war. Will need a big yard with a secure fence and a family who wants to exercise with him everyday. Goes right into his crate with a treat.

If interested in meeting or adopting Dugan, please fill out an app on our website at www.tgspca.org

animal.description:
Mario is a deaf and blind Australian Shepherd who is about a year and a half. 
Mario was adopted from us as a puppy and then surrendered back to us in awful condition. We’ve spent the last few months helping him gain weight, get properly groomed, and learn all about freedom! 

Mario is a sweet, sweet boy who loves all people and animals. He does well in his crate and has been working very hard on house breaking. He is still on a puppy type schedule and can only go for a few hours before having an accident, but this is improving now that he’s been in a foster home that’s keeping him on track. 

Mario would do well in a home with or without other dogs, but would love dog friends if his new family doesn’t already have pets. He would do well in a home with older children because he is blind and can easily knock over a small child when excited. His new family should be prepared to continue working with him on training (with our help!) and helping to keep his mind busy! 

He is searching for a home within a few hours of Baltimore. 
If you think you’d be a good fit, please apply at kellerscause.com/adopt

He was found as a stray.. He is a bit smaller than he looks in this picture. He weighs about 40 lbs. This guy loves attention. You can visit our website or pricing and adoption details. The first step in our adoption process is completely filling out an adoption application. We are a foster based organization and do not currently have a shelter location.

Lucinda likes hiking and proudly prancing, but still she's alert and doesn't miss a squirrel or rabbit in the area. 
Lucinda will do best as an only pet and would be an amazing addition for a home with fenced yard. 


Adoption Fee is $350
She is up to date on vaccines and has had a wellness exam, heartworm tested and micro-chipped.
